        { title: "Redondo Beach", displayTitle: "Redondo Beach", duration: "3:29", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A reggae-inflected song about a woman found drowned on the California coast, told with an eerie, detached beauty that is more disturbing than any direct description — an early demonstration of Smith's ability to use musical lightness to carry dark content." },
        { title: "Birdland", displayTitle: "Birdland", duration: "9:15", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "At over nine minutes, this stream-of-consciousness centerpiece — inspired by Peter Reich's memoir about his father, scientist Wilhelm Reich — is the most ambitious track on the album, building from spoken-word poetry to ecstatic rock improvisation and back." },
        { title: "Free Money", displayTitle: "Free Money", duration: "3:52", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A song built around Smith's mother's lottery dream of financial freedom — it transforms working-class longing into something visionary through Smith's incantatory delivery over Richard Sohl's piano." },
        { title: "Kimberly", displayTitle: "Kimberly", duration: "4:29", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Written about the night Smith's younger sister Kimberly was born, this is one of the album's most personally tender tracks, unusual in a record that often operates at a high pitch of intensity." },
        { title: "Break It Up", displayTitle: "Break It Up", duration: "4:04", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Co-written with Television guitarist Tom Verlaine, this song describes a vision of Jim Morrison rising from the dead — a signature example of Smith weaving literary mythology, personal vision, and rock history into a single track." },
        { title: "Land", displayTitle: "Land", duration: "9:25", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The album's most complex and structurally adventurous track, a three-part suite that moves through surrealist narrative, a cover of Chris Kenner's 'Land of a Thousand Dances,' and a maritime poem — running over nine minutes and encompassing the album's full artistic range." },
        { title: "Elegie", displayTitle: "Elegie", duration: "4:04", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The album closes with a sparse elegy dedicated to Jimi Hendrix, written on the anniversary of his death — Smith's voice barely above a whisper, the band stripped to almost nothing, ending Horses in grief rather than triumph." }
