        { title: "Mind", displayTitle: "Mind", duration: "2:59", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A paranoid, circling track about the terror of thought itself — Byrne's delivery perfectly calibrated between genuine anxiety and deadpan absurdism, which is the album's characteristic tone." },
        { title: "Paper", displayTitle: "Paper", duration: "2:47", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "" },
        { title: "Cities", displayTitle: "Cities", duration: "4:07", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A rhythmically propulsive track about searching for the right city to live in that captures the specific anxiety of urban life in late-1970s America — Brian Eno's production gives it a slightly inhuman, mechanical energy." },
        { title: "Life During Wartime", displayTitle: "Life During Wartime", duration: "3:44", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Released as a promotional single, this became the album's signature track — Byrne describing survival in an imaginary urban wartime with specific, mundane details ('no time for music or the arts') that made the surreal feel documentary." },
        { title: "Memories Can't Wait", displayTitle: "Memories Can't Wait", duration: "3:37", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A nightmarish, disorienting track — perhaps the album's most unsettling — in which memory becomes a source of dread rather than comfort; Eno's production here is particularly atmospheric and claustrophobic." },
        { title: "Air", displayTitle: "Air", duration: "3:41", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Byrne singing about his fear of air — making the most fundamental fact of existence threatening through obsessive repetition — is both funny and genuinely unsettling, which is exactly what the album is aiming at." },
        { title: "Heaven", displayTitle: "Heaven", duration: "4:10", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The album's most unexpected track — a slow, beautiful song about a perfect bar where the same band plays the same song forever — the one moment where the album allows itself open tenderness, making it all the more affecting for the contrast." },
        { title: "Animals", displayTitle: "Animals", duration: "3:43", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Byrne's paranoid fear of animals expressed as a kind of reverse anthropomorphism — the animals are watching and judging — delivered over a tightly interlocking rhythm track that itself sounds slightly animal." },
        { title: "Electric Guitar", displayTitle: "Electric Guitar", duration: "3:52", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A meta-commentary on the electric guitar itself as an object of cultural anxiety — notable on an album by a rock band that was deliberately questioning rock music's own conventions." },
        { title: "Drugs", displayTitle: "Drugs", duration: "5:17", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The album's closing track is its most extreme — a seven-minute dissociative loop in which drug imagery becomes a metaphor for the loss of self and coherence, built on interlocking instrumental parts that feel genuinely destabilizing." }
