    historicalContext: "Kid A was released in October 2000, three years after OK Computer had made Radiohead the most critically lauded rock band in the world. In the intervening period, Thom Yorke had suffered a breakdown from the pressures of touring and success, and the band spent months unable to write conventional songs. Instead, they dismantled the rock format entirely — buying synthesizers, studying electronic music, and working with producer Nigel Godrich in a way that treated the recording studio as the instrument. The album arrived at the hinge point between the CD era and the digital music era; it was widely leaked online before release, and the internet discussion that followed became one of the earliest examples of the way music discourse would move entirely online. The album's themes of dehumanization, alienation, and the end of recognizable structures felt precise for the year 2000 — the millennium's uncertain morning-after.",
