      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "Berry Gordy initially refused to release the album, calling it 'the worst thing I ever heard' — it became Motown's fastest-selling single ever within weeks.",
          "The party sounds at the start of the title track came from an actual gathering of Detroit Lions football players at a real party Gaye attended.",
          "Gaye played all three drum kit parts himself, layering them to get an unusual rhythmic feel.",
          "The 33⅓ book on this album was written by music journalist Ben Edmonds, who knew Gaye personally."
      ],
      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "What's Going On",
              "note": "The opening title track sets the tone with its seamless flow, layered vocals, and the sound of a party transitioning into a lament — essential for understanding how the album works."
          },
          {
              "title": "Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)",
              "note": "A strikingly modern song about environmental destruction that sounds as relevant today as it did in 1971."
          },
          {
              "title": "Inner City Blues (Make Me Wanna Holler)",
              "note": "The album's most stripped-down and raw closer — a slow, grinding groove that captures urban despair with no sentimentality."
          }
      ],
      "tracklist": [
        { title: "What's Going On", displayTitle: "What's Going On", duration: "3:53", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Originally rejected by Motown as uncommercial, this Vietnam-era protest song became a #2 pop hit and is regularly cited as one of the greatest songs ever recorded, its polyphonic vocal layers and jazz-inflected arrangement unlike anything Motown had released before." },
        { title: "What's Happening Brother", displayTitle: "What's Happening Brother", duration: "2:43", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Written from the perspective of a returning Vietnam veteran struggling to reintegrate into civilian life, the track gives the album's political concerns a deeply personal, street-level voice." },
        { title: "Flyin' High (In the Friendly Sky)", displayTitle: "Flyin' High (In the Friendly Sky)", duration: "3:49", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A languorous, melancholic portrait of drug addiction — specifically heroin — that uses the language of flight as a metaphor for escape, addressing substance abuse with unusual directness for a major label release in 1971." },
        { title: "Save the Children", displayTitle: "Save the Children", duration: "4:03", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A plea for investment in the next generation that extends the album's social vision beyond Vietnam to poverty and environmental collapse, woven seamlessly into the album's continuous song-suite structure." },
        { title: "God Is Love", displayTitle: "God Is Love", duration: "1:41", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "" },
        { title: "Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)", displayTitle: "Mercy Mercy Me (The Ecology)", duration: "3:16", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "One of the earliest major pop hits to address environmental destruction, its lush orchestration and anguished vocal performance make ecological crisis feel personal and urgent rather than abstract." },
        { title: "Right On", displayTitle: "Right On", duration: "7:22", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The album's longest and most jazz-influenced track, its extended instrumental passages — featuring a Miles Davis-influenced trumpet — demonstrate how Gaye was pushing Motown's production vocabulary toward art music." },
        { title: "Wholy Holy", displayTitle: "Wholy Holy", duration: "3:09", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A gospel-drenched call for collective spiritual and social renewal that bridges the album's political and religious themes, its choir arrangement rooting the protest record in the Black church tradition." },
        { title: "Inner City Blues (Make Me Wanna Holler)", displayTitle: "Inner City Blues (Make Me Wanna Holler)", duration: "5:24", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The album's furious closer catalogues urban poverty, police brutality, and systemic neglect over a brooding, hypnotic groove that influenced soul, funk, and hip-hop producers for decades afterward." }
      ],
