      "historicalContext": "Unknown Pleasures was released in June 1979 on Factory Records in Manchester, a city hit hard by industrial decline and high unemployment. The punk movement had already happened; post-punk bands like Joy Division were exploring what came after anger — alienation, introspection, and art. Factory Records was a DIY label with no conventional contracts, run by TV presenter Tony Wilson. The album was pressed in an initial run of only 10,000 copies and barely charted, yet it became one of the most studied and influential debut albums in rock history.",
