      "contentNotes": {
          "language": "none",
          "themes": "Romantic love, heartbreak, self-reliance, friendship — all handled with warmth and maturity appropriate for any age.",
          "artworkConcern": "",
          "cleanVersionAvailable": "",
          "teacherDecision": ""
      },
      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "Tapestry spent 15 years on the Billboard 200 chart — 302 weeks total — a record that stood until the 1980s.",
          "The album was recorded in just a few weeks; King has said the sessions were unusually relaxed because everyone in the room were old friends.",
          "The 33⅓ book on this album was written by Judith Peraino and explores the album's place in feminist music history and the singer-songwriter tradition.",
          "James Taylor, who plays guitar on the album, was dating Joni Mitchell at the time and introduced her to the Laurel Canyon community that shaped Tapestry's sound."
      ],
      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "I Feel the Earth Move",
              "note": "The album's most energetic opener — an irresistible piano-and-drums groove that immediately establishes King as a performer, not just a songwriter."
          },
          {
              "title": "(You Make Me Feel Like) A Natural Woman",
              "note": "Originally a massive hit for Aretha Franklin, King's quieter, more personal version reveals how differently a song can land when sung by its own composer."
          },
          {
              "title": "It's Too Late",
              "note": "A Grammy-winning single about the end of a relationship — the adult emotional realism of its lyrics was unusual for pop radio in 1971."
          }
      ],
      "tracklist": [
        { title: "I Feel the Earth Move", displayTitle: "I Feel the Earth Move", duration: "2:56", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Released as one half of a double A-side with 'It's Too Late' that reached #1, this opening track's urgent piano groove and instantly memorable hook announced Tapestry as something more viscerally exciting than the soft-singer-songwriter category it was initially placed in." },
        { title: "So Far Away", displayTitle: "So Far Away", duration: "3:55", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A B-side to 'Smackwater Jack' that still charted, this reflective meditation on distance and longing showed King's gift for distilling complex emotional states into conversational, unadorned language." },
        { title: "It's Too Late", displayTitle: "It's Too Late", duration: "3:53", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The A-side of a #1 double single and one of the most acclaimed break-up songs in pop history, its laid-back groove and unflinching lyrical honesty — acknowledging mutual fault without melodrama — set a new standard for adult songwriting." },
        { title: "Home Again", displayTitle: "Home Again", duration: "2:29", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "" },
        { title: "Beautiful", displayTitle: "Beautiful", duration: "3:05", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A simple, affirming song about self-worth that has found renewed life as an anthem in school and therapeutic settings, its directness making it among King's most pedagogically resonant compositions." },
        { title: "Way Over Yonder", displayTitle: "Way Over Yonder", duration: "4:47", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "One of the album's most gospel-inflected moments, this track draws on the African-American spiritual tradition King absorbed through her years writing for Brill Building artists and reveals the depth of her musical range." },
        { title: "You've Got a Friend", displayTitle: "You've Got a Friend", duration: "5:06", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "Written in a single sitting, this song is the rare case of a songwriter's own version being eclipsed by a cover — James Taylor's recording reached #1 the same year — yet King's piano-led original has a directness Taylor's polished version slightly softens." },
        { title: "Where You Lead", displayTitle: "Where You Lead", duration: "3:18", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "" },
        { title: "Will You Love Me Tomorrow", displayTitle: "Will You Love Me Tomorrow", duration: "4:10", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "King co-wrote this song with Gerry Goffin in 1960, when The Shirelles recorded it as the first #1 by a Black girl group; here she reclaims it eleven years later as a slower, more personal reading, giving students a direct lesson in how a song evolves across different contexts." },
        { title: "Smackwater Jack", displayTitle: "Smackwater Jack", duration: "3:42", single: true, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "A tongue-in-cheek Western narrative co-written with Goffin that stands out on Tapestry for its uptempo country-blues feel, demonstrating King's stylistic versatility beyond the introspective ballads the album is best remembered for." },
        { title: "Tapestry", displayTitle: "Tapestry", duration: "3:13", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "The quietly beautiful title track, with just King's voice and acoustic guitar, serves as the album's philosophical core — its image of a life woven from experiences both painful and joyful gives the record its defining metaphor." },
        { title: "(You Make Me Feel Like) A Natural Woman", displayTitle: "(You Make Me Feel Like) A Natural Woman", duration: "3:58", single: false, explicit: false, hiddenFromStudentView: false, teacherNote: "King co-wrote this song for Aretha Franklin in 1967, and her own stripped-back piano version here stands as one of the most powerful acts of authorial reclamation in the singer-songwriter era — a reminder that the song's greatest interpreter may also be its creator." }
      ],
