      "historicalContext": "Harvest arrived in early 1972, a moment when the utopian dreams of the 1960s counterculture had curdled into disillusionment. The Vietnam War continued, political scandal was building toward Watergate, and the communal optimism of Woodstock felt distant. Young's quiet, personal songs — about love, solitude, and the passage of time — felt like a retreat inward, and millions of listeners retreated with him. The album's success also reflected growing public appetite for acoustic music as a reaction against the excess of arena rock.",
