      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Have you ever heard a song that felt like it was about something much bigger than the singer's personal life — about history, justice, or an entire people's experience? What was it?",
          "activity": "With a partner, think of one word that describes the feeling of 'Exodus' or 'Jamming' after a first listen. Share with the class."
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "Listen to the bass and drums — in reggae, the bass guitar carries as much melody as the lead instruments. Notice how it locks in with the kick drum.",
          "Pay attention to the guitar: it plays on the offbeat (the 'and' of each beat) rather than the downbeat. This 'skank' rhythm is the defining sound of reggae.",
          "The album splits into two halves — the first is more spiritual and political, the second more celebratory and romantic. Notice the shift.",
          "Think about the historical moment: Marley was recording this in London after an assassination attempt on his life in Jamaica. Does that context change how you hear the songs?"
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Time magazine named Exodus the Album of the Century in 1999, calling it the most important record of the twentieth century.",
          "The album stayed on the UK charts for 56 consecutive weeks — an unbroken record at the time — demonstrating how deeply reggae had penetrated mainstream global culture.",
          "Exodus introduced Rastafari beliefs, Jamaican history, and the concept of 'Babylon' (systemic oppression) to millions of listeners worldwide who had never encountered them before.",
          "Lloyd Bradley's 33⅓ book on Exodus examines how Marley transformed a Jamaican regional music into a global spiritual and political force."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "In December 1976, two gunmen entered Bob Marley's Kingston home and shot him, his wife Rita, and his manager Don Taylor. Marley survived but left Jamaica for London, where he recorded Exodus in a creative outpouring over four months. The album was made in exile — both physically and spiritually — and its title track draws on the Old Testament story of the Israelites' escape from Egypt as a metaphor for the Black diaspora's search for freedom from oppression. Released in 1977 during a period of rising punk in the UK and ongoing political violence in Jamaica, Exodus crossed all boundaries.",
