      "soundAndStyle": {
          "genre": "Trip-Hop / Downtempo / Electronic Soul",
          "mood": "Melancholy, cinematic, hypnotic, haunting, tense, intimate",
          "mainSounds": "Sampled and looped breakbeats, wah-wah guitar, analogue synthesizers, vinyl crackle, live orchestral samples, theremin, Beth Gibbons's trembling vocals",
          "productionStyle": "Meticulous and layered — Geoff Barrow sampled obscure film soundtracks and jazz records, then re-recorded the samples to create original source material that was then re-sampled. All scratching performed live by DJ.",
          "energy": "Consistently low and slow — tension comes not from speed but from texture, space, and the feeling of something unsaid",
          "keyIdea": "Dummy turns sadness and urban alienation into something beautiful by treating every sonic element — a scratch, a string sample, a breath — as part of one sustained emotional statement."
      },
      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Can you think of a film, TV show, or video game where the music made the scene feel completely different than it would have without it? What was it about the music that did that?",
          "activity": "Close your eyes while 'Sour Times' plays for 60 seconds. With a partner, describe what you imagined — a place, a colour, a scene."
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "Listen for the vinyl crackle and surface noise — Portishead deliberately built this into the music to make digital recordings feel analogue and worn.",
          "Pay attention to Beth Gibbons's voice. She rarely sings conventionally — listen for the tremor, the catch in her breath, the places where her voice seems about to break.",
          "Notice how the beats feel different from regular drum kit playing. These are 'breakbeats' — sampled from old records and looped. They feel slightly off, slightly delayed, and that creates the trip-hop feeling.",
          "Think about what kind of film this music would score. Film noir? A spy thriller? A late-night city scene? Why does it conjure those images?"
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Dummy won the 1995 Mercury Prize — the UK's most prestigious music award — and its victory introduced trip-hop to a mainstream audience that had never heard anything like it.",
          "The album sold over two million copies in the UK alone, making it the best-selling Mercury Prize winner to that point and proving that deeply atmospheric, unconventional electronic music could reach a huge audience.",
          "Dummy essentially defined the genre of trip-hop, a term used to describe the Bristol Sound of slow, sampled, emotionally dark electronic music that Portishead, Massive Attack, and Tricky created.",
          "RJ Wheaton's 33⅓ book on Dummy examines how Barrow, Utley, and Gibbons created the album's sound from scratch — including the technique of sampling their own re-recorded samples to avoid copyright issues."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "Dummy arrived in August 1994, at a moment when British music was simultaneously exploding with Britpop (Blur, Oasis, Pulp) and fracturing into dozens of experimental sub-genres. Bristol, the UK's sixth-largest city, had developed its own musical identity entirely separate from the London-based Britpop scene — darker, more electronic, more influenced by American hip-hop and soul than by British guitar-pop. Portishead, Massive Attack, and Tricky were the three acts who put Bristol on the global musical map. Dummy came the same year as Oasis's Definitely Maybe and Blur's Parklife, yet sounds nothing like either — a reminder of how radically diverse British music was in 1994.",
