      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Mannequin",
              "note": "The most accessible track on the album — it has something approaching a chorus. Compare it to the tracks around it and notice how much that single repeated hook changes the experience. Wire thought even this was too much; they stripped it further on later albums."
          },
          {
              "title": "Ex Lion Tamer",
              "note": "The album's most melodic moment — and the one that shows Wire could write a warm, engaging song; they simply chose not to most of the time. Does knowing that make the rest of the album feel like a choice or a limitation?"
          },
          {
              "title": "106 Beats That",
              "note": "A longer track by Pink Flag's standards — listen to how Wire builds tension through sheer repetition without adding anything new. What keeps you listening when almost nothing changes?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Reuters",
              "note": "The opener — two minutes of clipped, affectless description of conflict. Notice that Colin Newman's vocal delivers horrible content in a completely flat voice. What effect does that create? Is it more or less powerful than an emotional delivery would be?"
          }
      ],
