      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Pink Flag has 21 tracks, most under two minutes. Does hearing so many short, complete pieces back-to-back feel different from a normal album? Does brevity change how you engage with the music?",
          "Wire removed everything they considered unnecessary from their songs. What's the risk of that approach — and what's the gain? Is there something that gets lost when a song is stripped completely bare?",
          "The album was released in the same month as Never Mind the Bollocks by the Sex Pistols — both punk records, but wildly different approaches. Which feels more radical to you, and why?",
          "R.E.M., Minor Threat, and Elastica all cite Wire as a major influence. What does it mean for a band that didn't have major commercial success to be so influential — and does chart success matter when we assess how important a record is?"
      ],
