      "soundAndStyle": {
          "genre": "Alternative Rock / Art Rock",
          "mood": "Anxious, expansive, yearning, claustrophobic, occasionally euphoric",
          "mainSounds": "Layered electric guitars, distorted and clean in the same song; Thom Yorke's falsetto at full stretch; spare piano on ballads; driving rhythm section",
          "productionStyle": "Recorded partly with John Leckie and partly with Sean Slade and Paul Kolderie — the combination gives the album a mix of clean British polish and raw American urgency",
          "energy": "The album moves between enormous guitar explosions and fragile, exposed ballads — the contrast is the point",
          "keyIdea": "The Bends is the sound of a band discovering they could do anything, and nearly destroying themselves doing it."
      },
      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Think of a moment when you felt completely out of place in a room full of people — what did that feel like, and how would you describe it in a song?",
          "activity": "In pairs: each person names a song that feels overwhelming in the best possible way — the kind that almost drowns you. Share why. (2 min)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "Radiohead almost broke up making this album. Thom Yorke had a mental breakdown during the sessions, and the band had to restructure the recording process entirely.",
          "The title track was originally written as a B-side. The band started using a hospital oxygen mask on stage during the tour — Yorke said it was about the panic of suddenly being famous.",
          "'Fake Plastic Trees' was recorded in one take. Thom Yorke cried in the vocal booth, and the producer kept the take because the emotion was real.",
          "The 33⅓ book on The Bends was written by Alex Niven — it argues the album is the last great Britpop record and the first great post-Britpop one at the same time."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Established Radiohead as one of the most emotionally powerful rock bands in the world — not just another Britpop act.",
          "Rolling Stone and NME consistently rank it among the greatest albums of the 1990s; 'Fake Plastic Trees' and 'Street Spirit' remain among the most affecting songs of the era.",
          "'Street Spirit (Fade Out)' hit UK #5 — Thom Yorke has called it the saddest song he has ever written and said he has never been able to fully explain where it came from.",
          "The album proved that big guitar rock and intellectual, emotional depth were not opposites — a lesson Coldplay, Muse, and dozens of others absorbed immediately."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "Released in March 1995, The Bends arrived in the middle of Britpop's commercial peak — Blur and Oasis were dominating the UK charts with catchy, laddish guitar pop. Radiohead went in the opposite direction: enormous, emotionally raw, and uninterested in cool. The album was a commercial success but felt almost against the grain of its moment. Within two years, with OK Computer, they would redefine what British rock could be — but The Bends is where they first stopped caring what was fashionable.",
