      "beforeYouListen": [
          "RZA negotiated a deal with Loud Records that gave each Wu-Tang member the right to sign solo deals with any label. This was almost unheard of and turned the Clan into a business empire, not just a rap group.",
          "The album was recorded with cheap borrowed equipment. RZA has said the lo-fi quality was partly deliberate — he wanted the music to sound like it came from the street, not a professional studio.",
          "The 36 in the title refers to the 36 Chambers of the Shaolin Temple from kung-fu mythology — the album is saturated with references to kung-fu films, chess, and Five Percent Nation theology.",
          "The 33⅓ book on 36 Chambers was written by Gavin Mueller — it examines how a debut album recorded for almost nothing became one of the defining statements in hip-hop history."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Introduced nine distinct MC voices in a single album — an unprecedented collective structure that directly inspired Odd Future, ASAP Mob, and others.",
          "'C.R.E.A.M.' (Cash Rules Everything Around Me) became one of the most recognized rap songs in history and introduced the phrase into everyday American language.",
          "RZA's production — lo-fi soul samples, kung-fu dialogue, dirty drums — defined an East Coast aesthetic that defined mid-1990s hip-hop.",
          "Rolling Stone ranks it among the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time; it consistently appears on lists of the most important rap albums ever recorded."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers) was released in November 1993, the same year as Snoop Dogg's Doggystyle and De La Soul's Buhloone Mindstate — but it sounds like it came from a completely different world. While West Coast rap was dominating commercial radio with G-funk, Wu-Tang built something deliberately rough, mythological, and street-level. Staten Island was not a recognized hip-hop market; the album came from outside every established power structure in the industry and created its own.",
