      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Is there something you find it easier to express in writing, music, or art than you could ever say out loud? Why do you think that gap exists?",
          "activity": "In pairs: each person names one piece of music — song, film score, anything — that helped you through a difficult time. What did it do that words couldn't? (2 min)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "Tori Amos was dropped by her first label and told to give up music before she wrote this album. Little Earthquakes was the record that proved everyone who passed on her wrong.",
          "The track 'Me and a Gun' is performed entirely a cappella — no instruments at all, just her voice. It is one of the most powerful and intense tracks on the album. Teacher preview of that specific track is strongly recommended.",
          "Kate Bush is Amos's most cited influence — if you listened to Hounds of Love (week 79), notice how Amos takes the piano-centred art pop framework and makes it completely her own.",
          "The album reached #54 in the US but was a much bigger hit in the UK — it eventually went platinum in multiple countries as word spread slowly and steadily, without a massive radio hit driving it."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Little Earthquakes is one of the defining debut albums of 1990s alternative music — arriving a year before the wave of female singer-songwriters who followed.",
          "It demonstrated that a piano-centred alternative album could find a passionate audience outside mainstream pop radio.",
          "'Me and a Gun,' a bare a cappella song about sexual assault, remains one of the most discussed examples of an artist using music to directly address trauma — and one of the reasons RAINN (the US sexual assault support network) was founded, in part inspired by Amos's advocacy.",
          "Rolling Stone ranked it among the greatest debut albums in rock history, and it regularly appears on lists of the most important albums of the 1990s."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "January 1992 arrived in a moment of musical transition — Nirvana's Nevermind had just hit #1, alternative rock was crashing the mainstream, and the music industry was scrambling to understand what audiences wanted. Little Earthquakes was not part of any wave or trend: it was a young woman sitting at a piano, playing with the ferocity of a rock guitarist, and saying things into a microphone that no one in popular music had said quite so directly. The UK heard it first and heard it loudly; American audiences caught up over years.",
