      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "Amos was rejected by her record label after her first album (Y Kant Tori Read, 1988) and spent years being told she should pursue a different direction before making Little Earthquakes.",
          "The song 'Me and a Gun' was partly inspired by Amos's own experience of sexual assault — it is performed completely a cappella, with no accompaniment, making it one of the most stark and direct songs on any major-label debut.",
          "The album's biggest UK singles — 'Crucify' (#15), 'Winter' (#25), and 'Silent All These Years' (#26) — all charted without the album ever having a massive radio hit, demonstrating the power of word-of-mouth and late-night radio.",
          "The 33⅓ book on Little Earthquakes was written by Nathaniel Donahue, exploring the album's emotional architecture and its place in early-1990s alternative music."
      ],
