      "keyFacts": [
          "Reprise Records refused to release the album, calling it too experimental to sell. Wilco took the masters back and streamed it free on their website — 400,000 people downloaded it before Nonesuch signed them.",
          "The album debuted at #13 on the Billboard 200 on its official Nonesuch release — one of the strongest chart debuts of Wilco's career, proving the label wrong in the most public way possible.",
          "The documentary I Am Trying to Break Your Heart (2002), shot in black and white by Sam Jones, captured the making, the label dispute, and the firing of multi-instrumentalist Jay Bennett during the sessions.",
          "The 33⅓ book on Yankee Hotel Foxtrot was written by Mark Richardson, examining the album's recording process, its conceptual architecture, and its place in the history of American indie rock."
      ],
      "tracklist": [
          {
              "title": "I Am Trying to Break Your Heart",
              "displayTitle": "I Am Trying to Break Your Heart",
              "duration": "6:58",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's famous opening — seven minutes of a pop song slowly coming apart, with noise, studio manipulation, and a lyric that is simultaneously absurdist and tender. The documentary takes its name from this track. Not a commercial single but the key track on the album."
          },
          {
              "title": "Kamera",
              "displayTitle": "Kamera",
              "duration": "3:31",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A more immediately melodic track that offers some relief after the opener's disorientation — Tweedy's gift for a hook is clearest here."
          },
          {
              "title": "Radio Cure",
              "displayTitle": "Radio Cure",
              "duration": "4:48",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "Opens with a bass drone that undercuts the sweet melody sitting above it — Wilco's signature move of making something feel both comforting and wrong at the same time."
          },
          {
              "title": "War on War",
              "displayTitle": "War on War",
              "duration": "3:45",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "One of the album's most direct and accessible tracks — a reminder that underneath the experimental production is a fundamentally great song."
          },
          {
              "title": "Jesus, Etc.",
              "displayTitle": "Jesus, Etc.",
              "duration": "3:48",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's emotional centrepiece for many listeners — a string-led meditation on mortality and comfort that is among Tweedy's most beautiful compositions. Reportedly written shortly before 9/11."
          },
          {
              "title": "Ashes of American Flags",
              "displayTitle": "Ashes of American Flags",
              "duration": "5:07",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A slow, cinematic track that proved eerily resonant after 9/11, though it predates the attacks — its imagery of American symbols falling apart felt uncannily timely on release."
          },
          {
              "title": "Heavy Metal Drummer",
              "displayTitle": "Heavy Metal Drummer",
              "duration": "3:33",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "Promotional single. A sunlit, almost jubilant departure from the album's more unsettled moments — Tweedy looks back at adolescence with warm nostalgia. One of the most radio-friendly tracks, showing the range within the album."
          },
          {
              "title": "I'm the Man Who Loves You",
              "displayTitle": "I'm the Man Who Loves You",
              "duration": "3:14",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A muscular, driving rock track — the album's most straightforwardly energetic moment, which makes it feel like an outburst after all the restraint around it."
          },
          {
              "title": "Poor Places",
              "displayTitle": "Poor Places",
              "duration": "5:05",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "One of the album's most textured and atmospheric tracks — builds from a quiet folk song into something more ambient and unsettled. The shortwave voice saying 'Yankee Hotel Foxtrot' appears here."
          },
          {
              "title": "Reservations",
              "displayTitle": "Reservations",
              "duration": "5:48",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's closing track — a long, winding meditation on commitment and hesitation that refuses a clean resolution. It ends as it began: uncertain, searching, and beautiful."
          }
      ],
      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "I Am Trying to Break Your Heart",
              "note": "Seven minutes that include a pop song, ambient noise, studio manipulation, and an absurdist lyric that is also somehow a love song. Listen for the moment when it stops being a 'normal' song and ask yourself: when did that happen, and how did you feel when it did?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Jesus, Etc.",
              "note": "The album's heart. Listen to the strings — they were arranged to sound both consoling and slightly wrong. The lyric is about mortality and connection, and it works because it doesn't pretend to offer answers. This is what quiet confidence in a song sounds like."
          },
          {
              "title": "Heavy Metal Drummer",
              "note": "The most immediately accessible track — almost sunny. Notice how different it feels from the tracks around it. Ask whether that contrast is intentional, and what the band is doing by putting this moment of joy inside a much more anxious album."
          },
          {
              "title": "Ashes of American Flags",
              "note": "This song was written before 9/11. Listen to it knowing that — and then consider what it would have felt like to hear it for the first time in 2002. What does it mean when art describes something before it happens?"
          }
      ],
