      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Reprise Records said the album wouldn't sell and refused to release it. Wilco streamed it free online, 400,000 people downloaded it, and then it debuted at #13. What does that story tell us about who decides what music is valuable — and whether those people are always right?",
          "Several songs on this album were written before 9/11 but felt eerily relevant after it — especially 'Ashes of American Flags.' Does context change the meaning of art? Can a song mean something the artist didn't intend?",
          "The opening track 'I Am Trying to Break Your Heart' is seven minutes long and includes noise, distortion, and studio manipulation alongside a pop melody. Does that feel like too much — or does it do something that a shorter, cleaner song couldn't? What is the effect of the discomfort?",
          "Wilco gave the album away for free before it had an official release. If you made something you were proud of, would you rather give it away to reach as many people as possible, or sell it? Does the answer change if you need to pay rent?"
      ],
