      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Stand! (1969) is pure joy and optimism. This album, two years later, sounds like a completely different artist. What do you think happened? Is music a reliable document of how an artist is actually feeling?",
          "The title track is literally zero seconds of silence. Is this a cop-out, a profound statement, or something in between? What would it mean for a song about a riot to be silent?",
          "Sly Stone used a drum machine instead of his band's drummer, Greg Errico. In 1971, that was strange and alienating. Today drum machines and programmed beats are everywhere. Does knowing the history change how you hear modern hip-hop and R&B?",
          "This album was commercially successful despite being widely described as difficult and uncomfortable. What does that tell us about what listeners were looking for in 1971 — and about who was buying records?"
      ],
