      "artistOverview": "Bob Dylan arrived in New York City in 1961 as a folk singer in the tradition of Woody Guthrie, and within two years had become the voice of the civil rights and anti-war movements. By 1965 he was restless — he found the role of spokesman confining and was drawn to the electric rock and roll he had loved as a teenager. Bringing It All Back Home was his pivot: electric rock on Side 1, acoustic poetry on Side 2. It launched the folk-rock revolution and cost him half his audience — temporarily. Dylan has since been awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature.",
