      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "'Subterranean Homesick Blues' — the opening track — was shot as a film clip where Dylan holds up cue cards with the lyrics, dropping them one by one. It is considered the first music video, 15 years before MTV.",
          "The 33⅓ book on this album was written by Mark Polizzotti, examining how the album represented Dylan's break from his folk identity and his embrace of literary surrealism.",
          "The Byrds' cover of 'Mr. Tambourine Man' from this album reached #1 in both the US and UK in 1965, immediately establishing folk-rock as a genre. Dylan's own version — on Side 2, acoustic — is very different.",
          "Highway 61 Revisited is a separate album, also released in 1965, already in our library under a different ID. Do not confuse the two: Bringing It All Back Home came first, in March; Highway 61 came in August."
      ],
      "tracklist": [
          {
              "title": "Subterranean Homesick Blues",
              "displayTitle": "Subterranean Homesick Blues",
              "duration": "2:21",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "US #39, UK #9. Two minutes and twenty-one seconds of rapid-fire rhyming over an electric groove — widely cited as a precursor to rap. The famous cue-card film clip, shot by D.A. Pennebaker for the documentary Don't Look Back, is considered the first music video."
          },
          {
              "title": "She Belongs to Me",
              "displayTitle": "She Belongs to Me",
              "duration": "2:47",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A portrait song — Dylan paints a detailed picture of a woman without ever making the song explicitly about himself. The impressionistic technique is more novelist than folk singer."
          },
          {
              "title": "Maggie's Farm",
              "displayTitle": "Maggie's Farm",
              "duration": "3:55",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "UK #22. A raw electric blues about refusing to be exploited — widely read as Dylan's rebuke to the folk movement that had claimed him as its spokesman. The riff is loose and deliberately unpolished."
          },
          {
              "title": "Love Minus Zero/No Limit",
              "displayTitle": "Love Minus Zero/No Limit",
              "duration": "2:51",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "One of Dylan's most quietly beautiful love songs — the images are strange ('the cloak and dagger dangles') but the emotion is clear. A useful counterpoint to his more combative material."
          },
          {
              "title": "Outlaw Blues",
              "displayTitle": "Outlaw Blues",
              "duration": "3:05",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": ""
          },
          {
              "title": "On the Road Again",
              "displayTitle": "On the Road Again",
              "duration": "2:36",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A rolling comic blues — Dylan's surrealist absurdism in full effect, the imagery deliberately refusing to make conventional sense."
          },
          {
              "title": "Bob Dylan's 115th Dream",
              "displayTitle": "Bob Dylan's 115th Dream",
              "duration": "6:31",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The longest track on Side 1 — a shaggy-dog retelling of Columbus's voyage to America through Dylan's anarchic comic imagination. Famous for the false start at the opening where Dylan and the band fall out of sync and laugh."
          },
          {
              "title": "Mr. Tambourine Man",
              "displayTitle": "Mr. Tambourine Man",
              "duration": "5:29",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "UK #1 for The Byrds' cover version — Dylan's own recording was the B-side of his 'Subterranean Homesick Blues' single. On this album it opens Side 2 as a solo acoustic performance — dreamy, hallucinatory, and arguably his greatest lyric."
          },
          {
              "title": "Gates of Eden",
              "displayTitle": "Gates of Eden",
              "duration": "5:42",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A dense, relentless cascade of surrealist images — each verse piles on another impossible scene. Dylan biographer Robert Shelton called it the album's most complete artistic statement."
          },
          {
              "title": "It's Alright, Ma (I'm Only Bleeding)",
              "displayTitle": "It's Alright, Ma (I'm Only Bleeding)",
              "duration": "7:33",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's most politically charged track despite being fully acoustic — at 7:33, Dylan's sustained fury about advertising, conformity, and power has been cited by politicians and musicians alike for six decades."
          },
          {
              "title": "It's All Over Now, Baby Blue",
              "displayTitle": "It's All Over Now, Baby Blue",
              "duration": "4:13",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's farewell — widely interpreted as Dylan saying goodbye to his folk audience, his manager, or an ex-lover. Bare acoustic guitar, spare and final. Joan Baez heard it as addressed to her."
          }
      ],
      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Subterranean Homesick Blues",
              "note": "Two minutes and twenty-one seconds — and the opening of an entirely new kind of lyric writing. Listen for the speed and the rhymes: this is closer to hip-hop than to folk. The cue-card film clip Dylan made for this song is considered the first music video."
          },
          {
              "title": "Mr. Tambourine Man",
              "note": "The Byrds' cover went to #1 but Dylan's version — solo acoustic on Side 2 — is stranger and more personal. Compare the two if you can. What does a full-band arrangement add and what does it lose?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Maggie's Farm",
              "note": "A raw electric blues that most critics read as Dylan's message to the folk scene that had claimed him: 'I ain't gonna work on Maggie's farm no more.' Who is Maggie? Does it matter if the answer is deliberately unclear?"
          },
          {
              "title": "It's Alright, Ma (I'm Only Bleeding)",
              "note": "Seven and a half minutes of solo acoustic guitar and an unbroken torrent of imagery about advertising, conformity, and power. Richard Nixon used a line from this song in a speech. Presidents have quoted Bob Dylan's folk songs at political rallies. What does that say about how art gets absorbed?"
          }
      ],
