      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Runaway",
              "note": "The album's emotional core. It opens with a single piano note repeated 35 times before anything else happens — listen for how that choice sets you up for everything that follows. This is a nine-minute confession from someone who knows exactly what's wrong with them and doesn't know how to fix it."
          },
          {
              "title": "Power",
              "note": "Notice the sample: that guitar riff is from a 1969 progressive rock album by King Crimson. Kanye loops it into a hip-hop track and it sounds completely natural. How does using someone else's music from a different era and genre change what the new song means?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Monster",
              "note": "Listen to all four verses in sequence. Nicki Minaj performs in multiple different character voices — she essentially does three different rappers in 45 seconds. Why does her verse feel so different from the others, even when the production is identical?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Who Will Survive in America",
              "note": "The album ends with Gil Scott-Heron, a poet who was 70 years old and dying when this was recorded. Why would Kanye — making an album about his own excess and fame — choose to end with someone else's voice delivering a protest poem from 1970? What is he saying by closing this way?"
          }
      ],
