      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Think of a neighbourhood, street, or place you remember from childhood. What feeling comes back when you think about it now? Is that feeling the same as what you felt then?",
          "activity": "In pairs: describe one memory from childhood that feels different now that you're older — something that meant one thing then and means something else now. (2 min)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "The album is called Funeral because several members of the band lost family members while recording it. The deaths of grandparents and relatives are referenced directly in the lyrics. This is not a concept album about death — it's an album made by people who were actually grieving.",
          "Arcade Fire typically perform with seven or more people on stage, and most of them switch instruments between songs. When you listen, notice how many different sounds are layered — the band plays orchestral instruments (violin, cello, accordion, harp) alongside electric guitars and drums.",
          "Funeral was released on Merge Records, a small independent label based in Chapel Hill, North Carolina. It had almost no mainstream promotion. It spread entirely through word-of-mouth — music bloggers, indie record stores, personal recommendations. Within a year it was on every critic's album of the year list.",
          "David Bowie attended an early Arcade Fire concert in New York and reportedly told them they were the best band he had seen in years. He later joined them on stage at a festival. This endorsement helped break the band to a wider audience at a moment when Bowie's taste was still considered a significant cultural signal."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Funeral was named album of the decade by several publications including Pitchfork, NME, and Rolling Stone — an extraordinary achievement for a debut album released on an independent label with no mainstream marketing.",
          "The album helped legitimise indie rock as a form capable of genuine emotional seriousness — it showed that guitars and feelings and orchestral arrangements could coexist without any of them being sacrificed.",
          "It was one of the last great albums to spread almost entirely through word-of-mouth before social media changed how music discovery worked — its success demonstrated that great records could still find their audiences without commercial machinery.",
          "The 33⅓ book on Funeral was written by Eric Harvey, examining how the album's themes of community, memory, and collective grief captured a specific cultural moment in the early 2000s."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "Funeral was released in September 2004 — three years after September 11, and during a particularly fractious and anxious period in North American cultural life. The album's themes of lost neighbourhoods, childhood endings, and communal grief resonated with an audience that was processing both personal loss and a broader sense of cultural unease. Indie rock at the time was characterised by ironic detachment — Arcade Fire's sincerity and emotional directness felt like a rebuke to that pose. The album also appeared at the moment when music blogging was replacing print journalism as the primary vehicle for indie music discovery — Funeral was one of the first albums to become a phenomenon through blog-to-blog recommendation rather than magazine reviews.",
