      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Human Behaviour",
              "note": "The album opens with this. Notice who is doing the observing in the lyric — it's not a person watching the world, it's the reverse. How does flipping the perspective change what the song is saying? And what does the production — that slightly ominous, whirling electronic beat — add to the meaning?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Venus as a Boy",
              "note": "Björk plays the timpani herself on this track — those large percussion instruments you normally associate with classical orchestras. Listen for them underneath the strings. Why would she choose to perform rather than have a percussionist do it? What does that physical involvement add?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Violently Happy",
              "note": "The title is a paradox — happiness that feels violent, overwhelming, almost dangerous. Listen to how the production sounds: fast, driving, slightly out of control. Does the music match the title? Can music actually sound violently happy, or is that a contradiction the album is deliberately refusing to resolve?"
          },
          {
              "title": "There's More to Life Than This",
              "note": "This was recorded in the bathroom of a nightclub — you can hear the club noise in the background. Björk chose to include the ambient environment rather than edit it out. Why? What does the location add to the song? Is the bathroom of a club a meaningful setting, or is it just a joke?"
          }
      ],
      "releaseFacts": [
          {
              "label": "Runtime",
              "value": "51 min"
          },
          {
              "label": "Recorded",
              "value": "1992–1993, Compass Point Studios, Nassau; various London studios"
          },
          {
              "label": "Chart Peak (UK)",
              "value": "#3"
          },
          {
              "label": "Rolling Stone Rank",
              "value": "Top 500 Greatest Albums (2023)"
          }
      ],
      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Björk's voice has been described as 'unlike any other voice in popular music.' What does that actually mean? Is there such a thing as a voice that is objectively unique, or is uniqueness always relative to what you've already heard?",
          "The album mixes jazz standards from the 1940s, electronic dance production from the 1990s, orchestral arrangements, and a track recorded in a bathroom. Is that range a strength or a weakness? What would the album lose if it committed to just one style?",
          "Björk was an outsider in London — an Icelander in one of the world's biggest cities. The album is partly about that experience of newness and displacement. Do you think being an outsider in a place helps you see it more clearly, or does it make it harder to understand?",
          "Björk has always insisted on total artistic control — she co-produces, directs her own videos, and designs her stage shows. Is that kind of total control necessary for genuine artistic vision, or does collaboration and external input sometimes make work better?"
      ],
