      "artistOverview": "The Cure formed in Crawley, West Sussex, in 1976, built around the songwriting, guitar, and distinctive baritone vocals of Robert Smith. The band navigated through punk, post-punk, goth, and pop over a decade of releases before Disintegration, generally regarded as their creative peak. Smith wrote the album in a period of personal crisis — he was 29 and felt himself approaching 30 with a sense of collapse — and against the wishes of his record label, who wanted a follow-up to the commercially successful Kiss Me, Kiss Me, Kiss Me. The result was a 72-minute immersion in loss, despair, and longing that became paradoxically one of the band's biggest commercial successes.",
