      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Robert Smith wrote this album about his own depression and fear of turning 30. The record label hated it and wanted something more commercial. It became The Cure's best-selling album. What does that tell us about the relationship between artistic risk, commercial expectation, and what audiences actually want?",
          "Disintegration is 72 minutes long and almost entirely slow and dark. There are no upbeat tracks, no change of pace, no attempt to lighten the mood. Is that a weakness or a strength? What does sustained emotional consistency do that a varied record can't?",
          "'Lovesong' is the simplest, most direct track on the album — and the only one that reached #1. Does pop success require simplicity? Is there something dishonest about writing a straightforward love song in the middle of an album about despair, or is that contrast the point?",
          "The album's themes — depression, loss, the fear of getting older, the sense that something is ending — are things many people experience. Why might a record about those feelings make people feel less alone, rather than more depressed? What is it about shared sadness that is comforting?"
      ],
