      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Nightswimming",
              "note": "Piano alone, with John Paul Jones's string arrangement building around it. Listen to how the strings enter — not as decoration but as memory itself surfacing. The lyric is about skinny-dipping as teenagers and what it means to look back at that kind of freedom from the far side of adulthood."
          },
          {
              "title": "Everybody Hurts",
              "note": "Deliberately simple — almost aggressively so. The band stripped away everything complicated to make something that could reach anyone who needed it. Ask students: what does it mean to write a song this directly? Is simplicity a choice or a limitation?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Man on the Moon",
              "note": "A song about Andy Kaufman and the art of refusing to be pinned down. The refrain 'if you believe they put a man on the moon' links Kaufman's absurdist stunts with conspiracy thinking — Stipe leaves it deliberately ambiguous whether we're meant to believe or doubt."
          },
          {
              "title": "Drive",
              "note": "The opener — almost no production, Michael Stipe barely above a whisper. After Out of Time's polished pop, this was a signal: we are doing something different. Notice how slow and minimal it is compared to what you'd expect from a band at this level of fame."
          }
      ],
