      "discussionQuestions": [
          "R.E.M. were one of the biggest bands in the world when they made this album — they had nothing left to prove commercially. Does knowing that change how you hear their choice to make something so quiet and mournful?",
          "'Everybody Hurts' was used in suicide prevention campaigns. Can a pop song actually help someone who is suffering — or is that giving music too much credit?",
          "The album is full of references to mortality and old age, written by men in their early thirties. What does it mean to write about death before you're close to it? Is that insight or presumption?",
          "This is R.E.M.'s second album in our library — we heard Murmur (1983) earlier in the year. Nine years separate them. What does the difference between those two records tell you about how artists change?"
      ],
