      "beforeYouListen": [
          "We already heard Joni Mitchell's Blue in our library — that album is stark, solo, devastating. Court and Spark (1974) is three years later and sounds almost like a different artist: jazz musicians, horn arrangements, pop production. Same songwriter, completely different world.",
          "The backing band on much of this album is Tom Scott and the L.A. Express — a jazz-fusion group. Mitchell's use of real jazz musicians rather than rock session players gave the album a harmonic sophistication unusual for pop radio in 1974.",
          "'Help Me' reached #7 on the US pop charts — Mitchell's highest-charting single. The same woman who made Blue, which spent no time on the pop charts, suddenly had a Top 10 hit.",
          "The 33⅓ book on Court and Spark was written by Sean Nelson, who offers a detailed account of how Mitchell constructed the album's unusually complex song cycle."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Court and Spark was Joni Mitchell's commercial breakthrough — her highest-charting album and the record that proved jazz-influenced songwriting could reach a mainstream audience.",
          "It won two Grammy Awards in 1975 and is consistently ranked among the greatest albums ever made — Rolling Stone, NME, and many others place it in the top tier of the 1970s.",
          "The album demonstrated that a female artist could control her own production, use jazz harmony without alienating pop audiences, and write from her own experience without compromise.",
          "Mitchell's use of open guitar tunings throughout her career (she rarely used standard tuning) represents one of the most distinctive and influential technical approaches in rock songwriting."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "Released in January 1974, Court and Spark arrived at the height of the singer-songwriter era — a moment when personal, adult-oriented music dominated American rock. The early 1970s Laurel Canyon scene (Mitchell, James Taylor, Carole King, Jackson Browne) had shifted the center of gravity away from British rock toward California introspection. Mitchell's move toward jazz marked the beginning of an artistic evolution that would take her further and further from commercial convention through the rest of the decade.",
