      "contentNotes": {
          "language": "none",
          "themes": "Direct political attack on a military dictatorship. Historical context involves violence against civilians (the Kalakuta raid), the death of Fela's mother after soldiers threw her from a window, and Fela's repeated imprisonment. These themes are essential and very teachable — they are the point of the album, not incidental content. Teachers should brief students on the historical context before listening.",
          "artworkConcern": "",
          "cleanVersionAvailable": "",
          "teacherDecision": ""
      },
      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "Zombie has only two tracks — 'Zombie' (approx. 12 min) and 'Mister Follow Follow' (approx. 14 min). This is characteristic of Afrobeat: the groove is the architecture, and it requires extended time to work.",
          "After this album was released, approximately 1,000 Nigerian soldiers raided Fela's Kalakuta Republic commune. His mother, Funmilayo Ransome-Kuti, was thrown from a window and died months later from her injuries.",
          "Fela turned his mother's coffin over to the military government as a direct act of protest — and then recorded an album (Coffin for Head of State, 1981) about the experience.",
          "The 33⅓ book on Zombie was written by Gary Stewart, situating the album in the full context of Fela's life and the Nigerian political situation of the 1970s."
      ],
      "tracklist": [
          {
              "title": "Zombie",
              "displayTitle": "Zombie",
              "duration": "12:02",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The title track — a direct attack on Nigerian soldiers, described as mindless zombies who follow orders without thought ('Zombie no go go, unless you tell am to go'). The lyric is delivered over an interlocking Afrobeat groove built by Tony Allen's drums and a large horn section. This is the track that provoked the military raid on Fela's compound."
          },
          {
              "title": "Mister Follow Follow",
              "displayTitle": "Mister Follow Follow",
              "duration": "13:49",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's second side — an attack on ordinary Nigerians who comply with and enable the military's abuses rather than resisting. 'Mister Follow Follow' is Nigerian Pidgin for a person who blindly follows authority. The groove is slower and more hypnotic than 'Zombie,' giving the political argument more time to land."
          }
      ],
      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Zombie",
              "note": "This is twelve minutes of a single groove — drums, bass, horns, and a lyric that calls soldiers zombies by name. Listen to how the rhythm section locks together: Tony Allen's drums are doing something genuinely unusual (he is considered one of the most important drummers of the twentieth century). Ask yourself: why does this political argument need twelve minutes? What does time do to the message?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Mister Follow Follow",
              "note": "If Zombie attacks the soldiers, this track attacks the civilians who allow it to happen. 'Follow follow' in Nigerian Pidgin means to go along with whatever authority says. Fela is making the argument that complicity is its own form of corruption. Listen for how the groove softens slightly here — the accusation lands differently when it's directed at ordinary people rather than soldiers."
          }
      ],
