      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Fela made an album attacking the Nigerian military by name — and soldiers burned his home down in response. Most protest music is symbolic. This one got a military response. Does that make it more powerful as art, or just more dangerous as an act?",
          "'Zombie' compares soldiers to the undead — people who follow orders without thought. Is that a fair criticism of soldiers? When does following orders stop being acceptable?",
          "This album has two tracks, each over twelve minutes. Fela deliberately chose this form — no hit singles, no three-minute songs, no radio play. What does it mean to design music that resists being packaged and sold?",
          "Fela's mother was killed because of this album. He responded by making more music and turning her coffin over to the government as a protest. What does it mean to keep making art after something like that? What do you think kept him going?"
      ],
