      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Chicago",
              "note": "Start here if you want to understand what the album is doing emotionally. 'I made a lot of mistakes' — four words that open up the entire record. Notice how the orchestration builds underneath a lyric of regret rather than triumph."
          },
          {
              "title": "Casimir Pulaski Day",
              "note": "A friend dying of cancer, told in plain language. No metaphors, no abstractions — just the specific details of a hospital room and a person losing faith slowly. Notice how the banjo melody stays gentle even as the content becomes unbearable."
          },
          {
              "title": "John Wayne Gacy, Jr.",
              "note": "A song about a real murderer that turns into a self-examination. Listen closely to the final lines — Sufjan turns the camera on himself. What is he saying? Why does he end it that way?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Come On! Feel the Illinoise!",
              "note": "The album's most ambitious track — two completely different moods joined in one six-minute piece. The 1893 World's Fair section is ecstatic; the Carl Sandburg dream is intimate. Listen for how Stevens pivots between them."
          }
      ],
