      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "I Am a Scientist",
              "note": "The album's most famous track — listen for how a completely lo-fi recording with audible tape hiss can still deliver one of the most memorable choruses of the 1990s. The question to ask: does the roughness hurt the song, or is it part of what makes it feel real?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Tractor Rape Chain",
              "note": "Slower and more hypnotic than most tracks here — it is one of the few songs that takes its time. Notice how the melody stays with you after only one listen despite the brevity."
          },
          {
              "title": "A Salty Salute",
              "note": "This is what Pollard's basement recordings are reaching for — an anthem that feels enormous even though it was made with almost nothing. Listen for the emotional lift in the chorus and ask yourself: does knowing it was made on a 4-track change how you hear it?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Echos Myron",
              "note": "One of the longer tracks at 2:18 — by this album's standards, it is almost an epic. Listen to the way the tape warble affects the vocals and decide whether it sounds like a flaw or a feature."
          }
      ],
      "releaseFacts": [
          {
              "label": "Runtime",
              "value": "38 min"
          },
          {
              "label": "Recorded",
              "value": "1993–1994, Robert Pollard's basement, Dayton, Ohio (4-track cassette)"
          },
          {
              "label": "Chart Peak (US)",
              "value": "Did not chart — word of mouth and critical acclaim only"
          },
          {
              "label": "33⅓ Book",
              "value": "Bee Thousand by Marc Woodworth (2006)"
          }
      ],
      "discussionQuestions": [
          "Robert Pollard was a 4th-grade teacher recording these songs in his basement in his mid-30s — does knowing that change how you hear the music? Does age or circumstance change what we expect from an artist?",
          "Most of these songs are under 2 minutes. Does a song need to be long to say something meaningful? What is the shortest song you've heard that you felt was complete?",
          "The lo-fi tape hiss and distortion are clearly audible throughout. If someone gave Guided by Voices a professional recording budget, would Bee Thousand be a better album — or would something essential be lost?",
          "Pollard wrote dozens of songs for every album, choosing only the sharpest fragments. Does the feeling of abundance — that there are more ideas than you can hold onto — make the listening experience different from an album that has 10 carefully developed tracks?"
      ],
