      "artistYearsActive": "1979 – 1991, 2012 – 2015",
      "artistOverview": "The Replacements were a band from Minneapolis who were beloved by critics and their devoted fanbase precisely because they seemed incapable of doing what a successful band was supposed to do. They were notorious for drunk, chaotic live shows, wilfully uncommercial decisions, and a stubborn refusal to court radio or MTV. Their earlier independent albums — especially Let It Be (1984), already in this library — captured that wild energy. Tim was their major label debut on Sire Records, and it is both their most polished and most conflicted album: the songs are sharper, the production more radio-ready, but the band's contempt for the machinery of success comes through on every track.",
