      "historicalContext": "Released January 1968, at the height of the psychedelic Summer of Love hangover. While most bands were making more ornate, polished, commercial music, the Velvet Underground went in the opposite direction — rawer, louder, more confrontational. The album sold poorly and received little radio play. Verve Records was bewildered by it. But the musicians who heard it — particularly in the UK — absorbed it deeply; traces of White Light/White Heat run through punk, post-punk, noise rock, shoegaze, and experimental music right up to the present.",
