      "beforeYouListen": [
          "The album is structured as a fake pirate radio broadcast in the style of Radio London, one of the 'pirate' radio stations that broadcast British pop to the UK from ships in the North Sea in the 1960s. Fake commercials for real products — Heinz baked beans, Odorono deodorant, Medac spot cream — are placed between the songs.",
          "On the album's famous cover, Pete Townshend sits in a bathtub full of Heinz baked beans while Roger Daltrey holds a giant tin of Odorono deodorant. The images were entirely satirical — the band was mocking the idea of celebrity product endorsement at the height of the Summer of Love.",
          "'I Can See for Miles' — the album's biggest hit — was written by Pete Townshend specifically because he was frustrated that The Who weren't being taken seriously as a rock band. He described it as 'the best thing I ever wrote' at the time. It reached #10 in the UK and #9 in the US.",
          "The 33⅓ book on The Who Sell Out was written by John Dougan (2006) — it traces the album's conception, its pirate radio framework, and its place in the history of the concept album."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "One of the first rock albums to use a framing device — the fake pirate radio broadcast — to give the entire album a structural meaning beyond individual songs, helping establish the concept album as a viable rock format.",
          "The album's satirical commentary on commercialism and celebrity endorsement was more sophisticated than almost anything else in British rock in 1967 — and it still reads clearly today.",
          "'I Can See for Miles' is widely considered one of Pete Townshend's greatest songs and one of the most powerfully recorded tracks of the era — its multitracked guitar and Daltrey's vocal performance are extraordinary.",
          "The Who Sell Out was made the same year as Sgt. Pepper's — hearing both albums shows two completely different ways of taking the concept album idea seriously: the Beatles went inward and ornate; The Who went satirical and outward-facing."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "Released December 1967 — the same year as Sgt. Pepper's, Are You Experienced, and The Velvet Underground & Nico. The Summer of Love was ending and the British music scene was saturated with psychedelic music. The pirate radio stations that The Who Sell Out parodies were being shut down by the British government's Marine Broadcasting Offences Act, passed in August 1967 — the album appeared just as the thing it was satirising was being eliminated. Radio London went off the air three months before the album was released. The fake commercials were therefore both a satire and an elegy.",
