      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "I Can See for Miles",
              "note": "The album's most powerful track and biggest hit — listen for the way the multitracked guitars create a wall of sound and how Daltrey holds the vocal through it. Townshend said this was the best thing he ever wrote; when it peaked at #9 rather than #1, he felt the public didn't understand what they'd been given. Do you think it sounds like a #1 record?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Odorono",
              "note": "A song that is literally structured as a deodorant advertisement, but tells a real story about a singer losing her career because of a product failure. Notice how the satire and the genuine emotion coexist — is it possible to make fun of something and also mean it?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Pictures of Lily",
              "note": "A UK #4 hit about a boy who falls in love with a woman in a pin-up picture only to discover she died in 1929. Townshend plays the absurdity completely straight — no winking, no comic exaggeration. Does deadpan humour land better than obviously signposted jokes?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Tattoo",
              "note": "Two brothers getting tattoos — a small story told with real warmth and precision. Notice how much Townshend can do with a character portrait in under three minutes. What makes a short song feel complete?"
          }
      ],
