      "discussionQuestions": [
          "The album mocks commercialism by putting fake advertisements between the songs — but it also genuinely advertises products (Heinz, Odorono) and was sold commercially as a record. Can a satire of commerce also be a commercial product? Does that contradiction undermine the joke or make it more interesting?",
          "Pete Townshend said 'I Can See for Miles' was the best thing he ever wrote, and was devastated when it didn't reach #1. Should an artist's opinion of their own work change how we hear it?",
          "The pirate radio stations the album is based on were shut down by the British government three months before the album came out. Does it matter that the album is an elegy for something that no longer existed when it was released?",
          "Compare this album to Tommy (1969) or Who's Next (1971) — The Who went on to make some of the biggest rock albums of the 1970s. Does knowing that make The Who Sell Out seem like a stepping stone, or does it stand on its own?"
      ],
