      "soundAndStyle": {
          "genre": "Art Rock / Ambient / Experimental",
          "mood": "Mysterious, calm, otherworldly, occasionally playful, vast",
          "mainSounds": "Synthesizers, treated guitar, piano, sparse drums, gentle found sounds, Eno's deadpan vocals on the song-form tracks",
          "productionStyle": "Built using Oblique Strategies — a deck of cards with random instructions Eno used to generate unexpected musical decisions. Many tracks emerged from accident rather than intention.",
          "energy": "Quiet and unhurried — the album rewards attention but never demands it; the sound changes slowly and deliberately",
          "keyIdea": "Eno asked: what if atmosphere and texture were the subject of the music, not just the setting for a melody? This album is his answer."
      },
      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Can silence be part of a song? Can a sound that doesn't change for two minutes still be interesting? What makes something music versus just noise?",
          "activity": "Play thirty seconds of a purely textural track from the album with eyes closed. Ask students: what did you picture? What did you feel? (2 min)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "About half the tracks on this album have no vocals, no traditional melody, and no chord progression — they are purely about texture and atmosphere. Eno called this approach 'ambient music,' and this album is where the term was born.",
          "To write the instrumental pieces, Eno used a deck of cards called Oblique Strategies — each card had a random instruction like 'Honor thy error as a hidden intention' or 'Use an unacceptable color.' When he got stuck, he drew a card and followed it.",
          "Phil Collins, who would later become one of the best-selling pop artists of the 1980s, plays drums on this album. Robert Fripp, the cerebral guitarist from King Crimson, plays guitar. John Cale, founder of the Velvet Underground, plays viola.",
          "The 33⅓ book on this album was written by Marc Weidenbaum, founder of the ambient music website Disquiet. He argues this is the most important album in the history of electronic and ambient music."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Another Green World is the album where Brian Eno coined the concept of ambient music — music designed to be listened to actively or let wash over you, equally valid either way.",
          "The Oblique Strategies card method became one of the most widely used creative tools in rock and pop production — later used by Coldplay, David Bowie, and many others.",
          "The album's hybrid structure — half vocal songs, half pure texture — gave later artists a template for blending experimental and accessible approaches.",
          "Eno's production methods on this album directly shaped the Bowie Berlin Trilogy (Low, Heroes, Lodger) and Talking Heads' Remain in Light."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "By 1975, rock music was splitting in two directions: stadium bombast (Led Zeppelin, Queen) and stripped-down punk (just beginning to emerge). Eno was doing neither. He was working in a small studio with a handful of collaborators, making music that borrowed from German electronic music, modern classical composition, and pop song form all at once. Another Green World appeared the same year as Bruce Springsteen's Born to Run — an album about as different as possible. Both were influential; Eno's influence just took longer to become visible.",
