      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "This is the album where Brian Eno coined the term 'ambient music' — he defined it as music that can be either actively listened to or simply allowed to blend into the environment, and both experiences are valid.",
          "The instrumental tracks were composed using Oblique Strategies, a deck of instruction cards Eno created with artist Peter Schmidt. Drawing a card and following its instruction was part of the composition process.",
          "Phil Collins (later a huge 1980s pop star), Robert Fripp (King Crimson), and John Cale (Velvet Underground) all appear as session players — three very different musical worlds in one room.",
          "The 33⅓ book on this album was written by Marc Weidenbaum, who argues it is the single most important album in the history of ambient and electronic music."
      ],
