      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Can music be political just in how it sounds — not what the lyrics say, but how the guitar is played or how the rhythm is structured? Or does politics in music only come from the words?",
          "activity": "Name one song that made you think about something political or social — it doesn't have to be a protest song. What was it about the music or lyrics that did it? (2 min)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "Gang of Four were Leeds University students applying Marxist theory to music. Jon King and Andy Gill studied fine art and English lit; their lyrics treat consumer culture, desire, and power as subjects for analysis, not just feeling.",
          "'At Home He's a Tourist' was booked to appear on Top of the Pops — BBC's biggest pop TV show. The show asked them to change the word 'rubbers' in the lyrics (British slang for condoms). They refused. The performance was cancelled. The band has never expressed regret.",
          "Andy Gill's guitar style is one of the most imitated in post-punk history. He plays in short, percussive stabs with silence between them — influenced by James Brown's funk, but stripped of everything warm or smooth.",
          "The 33⅓ book on this album was written by Kevin J.H. Dettmar, a scholar who argues Entertainment! is one of the most intellectually serious rock records ever made."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Entertainment! is the foundational text of dance-punk — the sound that Red Hot Chili Peppers, Franz Ferdinand, and LCD Soundsystem all trace back to.",
          "Andy Gill's staccato guitar style became one of the most copied sounds in post-punk and alternative rock: angular, percussive, deliberately uncomfortable.",
          "The band's insistence on keeping 'rubbers' in 'At Home He's a Tourist' against BBC pressure was one of the most prominent censorship standoffs in British pop history.",
          "Rolling Stone named Entertainment! one of the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time — it is consistently cited as the most influential post-punk debut after the Sex Pistols."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "By 1979, British punk's first wave was largely spent. What followed — post-punk — was more exploratory, more intellectual, and more musically diverse. Gang of Four were part of a cluster of bands (Wire, The Fall, The Pop Group, Public Image Ltd.) that took punk's anti-commercial attitude and combined it with influences from funk, dub, and avant-garde art. Leeds and Manchester were the centers of this scene — far from London's fashion-punk. Entertainment! arrived in the same year as London Calling and Unknown Pleasures — three completely different visions of where rock music should go next.",
