      "soundAndStyle": {
          "genre": "Punk Rock / Post-Punk / Jazz-Punk",
          "mood": "Urgent, political, irreverent, communal, earnest",
          "mainSounds": "Tight, angular guitar chords; melodic, prominent bass; crisp jazz-influenced drumming; shouted or half-sung vocals; songs rarely exceeding two minutes",
          "productionStyle": "Dry, close-mic'd, almost live-sounding — no studio gloss. Recorded economically at SST studios. The sound is as stripped of excess as the songs themselves.",
          "energy": "Relentlessly energetic — 45 tracks in about 78 minutes. The density is the point: no filler, no solos, no wasted space. Like reading a book of very short, very sharp poems.",
          "keyIdea": "The Minutemen believed music should be democratically available — short enough that anyone could make it, cheap enough that any kid could buy it. 'We jam econo' was not just a financial necessity; it was a philosophy."
      },
      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "If you had to explain your entire worldview in under two minutes, what would you say — and do you think music is a good way to do that?",
          "activity": "Look up the speed limit on a major highway near you. Now: why would a band name their album '55 mph'? What could that possibly mean? (2 min discussion)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "This is a double album with 45 tracks. Most are under two minutes long. Think of it less like a regular album and more like a collection of short, sharp arguments.",
          "The title 'Double Nickels on the Dime' means 55 — as in 55 cents (two nickels = 10 cents, times 5.5... actually: a nickel = 5 cents, double nickels = 55 cents, i.e., 55 mph, the national speed limit in 1984). The cover photo shows them driving at exactly 55 mph on the freeway.",
          "D. Boon, Mike Watt, and George Hurley all grew up in San Pedro, CA — a working-class port town. They taught themselves to play and believed music was for regular people, not just trained musicians.",
          "D. Boon died in a van accident in December 1985 at age 27. The band immediately dissolved. This album is their masterpiece and their epitaph."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Rolling Stone ranked it #247 on the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time (2023) — a hardcore punk double album from an independent label holding its place in the canon.",
          "The album is a foundational document of American DIY punk: self-produced, self-released, self-distributed, self-sufficient. It proved that major-label infrastructure was not required to make a significant record.",
          "Its 45 tracks across four sides redefined what a double album could be — instead of excess, it offered compression. Every second is deliberate.",
          "A 33⅓ book devoted entirely to Double Nickels on the Dime was written by Michael T. Fournier, tracing the album's composition, recording, and cultural afterlife."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "In 1984, American hardcore punk was fracturing. Many of its founding bands were either breaking up or mellowing. The Minutemen responded not by slowing down but by accelerating — releasing a 45-track double album on SST Records, the independent label that also housed Hüsker Dü, Meat Puppets, and Black Flag. The national political climate — Reagan's America, Cold War anxiety, widening class inequality — pours directly into the album's lyrics. D. Boon and Mike Watt were not writing from a place of suburban alienation but from actual working-class lives in an industrial port town, and that specificity gives the record a grounded urgency that most punk of the era lacked.",
