      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "Double Nickels on the Dime contains 45 tracks spread across four sides of vinyl — most are under two minutes, making it one of the densest and most concentrated double albums ever recorded.",
          "The title refers to the 55 mph national speed limit: 'double nickels' = 55 cents = 55 mph. The cover photograph shows the band members driving at exactly 55 mph on a California freeway — a parody of Van Halen's 'Panama' video.",
          "D. Boon, Mike Watt, and George Hurley grew up together in San Pedro, CA, and taught themselves to play. They lived by the motto 'we jam econo' — meaning they made music cheaply, toured in a van, and kept the cost of attending their shows low so any kid could afford a ticket.",
          "A 33⅓ book dedicated to Double Nickels on the Dime was written by Michael T. Fournier, examining how the album's compression of ideas into tiny songs became a model for independent music-making."
      ],
