      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "History Lesson — Part II",
              "note": "The emotional heart of the album. Mike Watt recounts how he and D. Boon became who they were through friendship and shared records. It's about how music makes people — listen to whether it sounds like nostalgia or something more urgent."
          },
          {
              "title": "Corona",
              "note": "A tight, melodic burst that later became the Jackass theme. Listen for how it manages to sound joyful without losing any of the political compression the rest of the album has. It's also a good example of how a 70-second song can feel complete."
          },
          {
              "title": "This Ain't No Picnic",
              "note": "A complaint about the humiliation of boring work — listen to whether it sounds angry, funny, or both, and what the bass is doing under D. Boon's guitar. Watt's bass lines on this album aren't support instruments; they're equal voices."
          },
          {
              "title": "Political Song for Michael Jackson to Sing",
              "note": "50 seconds. Listen to how much they pack into it — and what the joke of the title tells you about the gap between the kind of political music that gets radio play and the kind they were making."
          }
      ],
