      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Something I Learned Today",
              "note": "The opening salvo — from the first few seconds, you understand what this record is going to feel like. Listen to how Mould's guitar manages to be melodic and abrasive at the same time. The hook is in there, buried under the distortion."
          },
          {
              "title": "Pink Turns to Blue",
              "note": "Grant Hart's most devastating song — a quiet, beautiful melody about something terrible. Listen to how the softness of the music works against the weight of the subject. Does restraint make it more or less affecting than if they'd screamed it?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Never Talking to You Again",
              "note": "The only acoustic track on a ferociously loud record. Notice what happens to the emotional temperature when the distortion disappears. Does the quietness feel like relief, or does it make the record feel more threatening by contrast?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Reoccurring Dreams",
              "note": "14 minutes of ambient instrumental at the end of a 23-track punk double album. Listen for how long it takes you to stop waiting for something to happen — and what you feel once you accept that this is where the story ends."
          }
      ],
