      "beforeYouListen": [
          "'When Doves Cry' has no bass line. Prince deliberately removed it after recording the full track — he felt it sounded like everything else, and wanted something that sounded like nothing else. It went to #1 for four weeks. Listen for the absence.",
          "Purple Rain was both a film and an album released simultaneously in the summer of 1984. The film is semi-autobiographical — Prince plays a character called 'the Kid.' You don't need to see the film to understand the album, but knowing it exists gives you context.",
          "The song 'Darling Nikki' contained lyrics that Tipper Gore found while her daughter was listening to the album. It directly led to the creation of the PMRC (Parents Music Resource Center) and the Parental Advisory sticker that you still see on albums today.",
          "In 1984, Michael Jackson's Thriller and Prince's Purple Rain were competing directly — both were massive, both were redefining what pop could be. They represent two very different answers to that same question."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "'When Doves Cry' spent four weeks at #1 and became the best-selling single of 1984 in the United States — its removal of the bass line made it one of the most distinctive-sounding #1 hits in pop history.",
          "'Darling Nikki' directly prompted Tipper Gore to create the PMRC, which led to the Parental Advisory sticker — a piece of music industry policy that came directly from a response to this album.",
          "Purple Rain won two Academy Awards (Best Original Song Score), a Grammy for Best Rock Performance, and a Golden Globe — the only album in these notes that intersects with film in this way.",
          "Rolling Stone ranked Purple Rain #18 on the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time (2023), making it Prince's highest-ranked album and one of the defining records of 1980s pop."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "The summer of 1984 was one of the most competitive moments in pop history. Michael Jackson's Thriller was still selling millions of copies. Madonna was ascending. Bruce Springsteen released Born in the USA the same week as Purple Rain. Into this environment, Prince released a film and album simultaneously — the film opened at #1, the album debuted at #1, and 'When Doves Cry' was already #1 on the singles chart. It was an unprecedented commercial moment. Politically, the PMRC battle over lyrics censorship began the following year directly in response to this album, making Purple Rain a document not just of 1984 pop culture but of the culture wars that followed.",
