      "contentNotes": {
          "language": "mild",
          "themes": "\"Darling Nikki\" contains sexually explicit lyrical content (masturbation reference) and was the direct catalyst for the PMRC and Parental Advisory sticker. Teacher should note this track specifically and decide whether to address it in class. The rest of the album is classroom appropriate.",
          "artworkConcern": "",
          "cleanVersionAvailable": "",
          "teacherDecision": ""
      },
      "classroomSafeMode": true,
      "keyFacts": [
          "'When Doves Cry' has no bass line — Prince removed it after recording the full track because he felt it sounded too conventional. It went to #1 for four weeks and became the best-selling single of 1984 in the US.",
          "'Darling Nikki' directly prompted Tipper Gore to found the PMRC (Parents Music Resource Center), which successfully lobbied the recording industry to introduce the Parental Advisory sticker — now ubiquitous on albums with explicit content. The song's liner notes in Prince's original pressing dedicated it to 'Tipper Gore' in return.",
          "Purple Rain the film opened at #1 at the US box office, the album debuted at #1, and 'When Doves Cry' was already #1 on the singles chart — a simultaneous triple #1 across three different entertainment categories.",
          "A 33⅓ book devoted entirely to Purple Rain was written by Michaelangelo Matos, examining its production, cultural context, and relationship to the film."
      ],
      "tracklist": [
          {
              "title": "Let's Go Crazy",
              "displayTitle": "Let's Go Crazy",
              "duration": "4:39",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "The album's opening statement — begins with a spoken 'sermon' before exploding into one of the most euphoric guitar-driven funk-rock tracks of the decade. US #1 for two weeks. The extended guitar solo at the end is a deliberate arena-rock reference in the middle of a pop record."
          },
          {
              "title": "Take Me with U",
              "displayTitle": "Take Me with U",
              "duration": "3:54",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A gentle, orchestrated ballad featuring Apollonia on backing vocals. US #25. A deliberate tonal contrast to the aggression that opens the album — Prince demonstrating range within a single LP."
          },
          {
              "title": "The Beautiful Ones",
              "displayTitle": "The Beautiful Ones",
              "duration": "5:13",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "One of the album's most emotionally raw moments — a yearning ballad that escalates into near-breakdown by its end. Widely considered one of Prince's greatest vocal performances."
          },
          {
              "title": "Computer Blue",
              "displayTitle": "Computer Blue",
              "duration": "3:59",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "A showcase for the band's interplay, with Wendy and Lisa's contributions (a recurring spoken intro in the full film version) making it one of the most collaborative-feeling tracks on the album."
          },
          {
              "title": "Darling Nikki",
              "displayTitle": "Darling Nikki",
              "duration": "4:09",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": true,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "Contains explicit sexual content (masturbation reference in the opening lines) — this was the specific song Tipper Gore objected to after her daughter listened to the album, leading directly to the PMRC and the Parental Advisory sticker. Teacher should preview and decide how to address this track. The reverse-recorded section at the end is frequently cited as an early Christian music Easter egg."
          },
          {
              "title": "When Doves Cry",
              "displayTitle": "When Doves Cry",
              "duration": "5:54",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "US #1 for four weeks and the best-selling single of 1984. No bass line — Prince removed it to make the track sound like nothing else in pop. The drum machine pattern and the guitar lick became immediately iconic."
          },
          {
              "title": "I Would Die 4 U",
              "displayTitle": "I Would Die 4 U",
              "duration": "2:49",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "US #8. A minimalist, synth-driven chant — lyrically almost nothing, rhythmically irresistible. Prince was demonstrating how little a song needs to work if the groove is there."
          },
          {
              "title": "Baby I'm a Star",
              "displayTitle": "Baby I'm a Star",
              "duration": "4:24",
              "single": false,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "Originally released as a double A-side with 'I Would Die 4 U.' A gospel-funk declaration of self-belief — the euphoria of the track is entirely genuine. In the film, it's the moment of triumph."
          },
          {
              "title": "Purple Rain",
              "displayTitle": "Purple Rain",
              "duration": "8:41",
              "single": true,
              "explicit": false,
              "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
              "teacherNote": "US #2. An eight-minute devotional power ballad with one of rock music's most celebrated guitar solos. The studio version incorporates a live audience recording from First Avenue in Minneapolis. The song functions as a hymn, and it closes the album like a benediction."
          }
      ],
      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "When Doves Cry",
              "note": "The most structurally unusual #1 pop song of its decade — listen specifically for what isn't there. No bass. The drum machine and the guitar are carrying everything. Notice how the absence of something creates the space that makes the song distinctive."
          },
          {
              "title": "Purple Rain",
              "note": "Eight minutes and forty-one seconds. Listen to how the guitar solo builds — it doesn't arrive as a display of technique but as an emotional event. Does it feel like the song needed that much space, or does it earn every second?"
          },
          {
              "title": "Let's Go Crazy",
              "note": "It opens with a spoken sermon and ends with a two-minute guitar solo. For a #1 pop song, it's extremely weird — listen to how it disguises its strangeness inside an irresistible groove."
          },
          {
              "title": "Darling Nikki",
              "note": "A note of context: this is the song that directly caused the Parental Advisory sticker to exist. The teacher will address whether to play it in class. If you listen: notice that it ends with a backward-recorded section — what does it say when you reverse it?"
          }
      ],
