      "keySongs": [
          {
              "title": "Just Like Honey",
              "note": "The clearest entry point on the album — the melody arrives first, before the feedback builds. Try to hear the 1960s girl-group pop underneath the noise. This exact song plays over the closing scene of Lost in Translation; the use of it there tells you something about what this album is actually about."
          },
          {
              "title": "Never Understand",
              "note": "The debut single that introduced this sound to the world. The feedback is at its most overwhelming here. Listen to whether the wall of noise makes the melody feel protected or buried — and whether that difference matters."
          },
          {
              "title": "You Trip Me Up",
              "note": "The feedback is slightly lower in the mix here, and the pop structure is easier to follow. Listen to this one alongside 'Never Understand' and describe what the feedback is doing to the emotional experience of each song."
          },
          {
              "title": "In a Hole",
              "note": "Four minutes — the album's longest track. The noise drone here goes on long enough that your ear begins to accept it as normal. At what point did you stop hearing it as noise and start hearing it as texture? Notice when that switch happens."
          }
      ],
