      "soundAndStyle": {
          "genre": "Indie Rock / Post-Punk / Riot Grrrl",
          "mood": "Fierce, precise, urgent, exhilarating, occasionally vulnerable",
          "mainSounds": "Two interlocking guitars (no bass), Janet Weiss's powerful drumming, dual vocal attack — Corin Tucker's soaring vibrato against Carrie Brownstein's more conversational delivery",
          "productionStyle": "Produced by John Goodmanson — clean enough to hear the guitar interplay clearly, rough enough to preserve the live-band energy; each instrument sits in its own space and the absence of bass is audible as a structural choice, not an oversight",
          "energy": "Relentless and propulsive — the album runs 33 minutes and barely pauses; the energy is athletic, controlled, and exhilarating",
          "keyIdea": "Dig Me Out proved that two guitars and drums — played by three women with something to say — could make one of the most fully realized rock albums of the decade."
      },
      "icebreaker": {
          "question": "Have you ever felt like you had to prove you belonged somewhere — in a sport, a subject, a social group? What did you do, and how did it feel when it worked?",
          "activity": "In pairs: each person names one band or artist they think is underrated or overlooked. Why do you think they aren't more famous? (2 min)"
      },
      "beforeYouListen": [
          "Sleater-Kinney have no bass player — the two guitars cover both the melodic and rhythmic roles that in most rock bands are split between guitar and bass. Listen for how the guitars relate to each other.",
          "Janet Weiss joined for this album, completing the lineup — she is widely regarded as one of the best rock drummers of her generation. Listen to how her playing drives the songs forward.",
          "The band grew out of the Riot Grrrl movement in Olympia, WA — a feminist punk scene that insisted women's experiences and perspectives were central to rock music, not peripheral to it.",
          "A 33⅓ book on Dig Me Out was written by Anwen Crawford, examining the album as a statement about identity, desire, and what it meant to be a woman making rock music in the 1990s."
      ],
      "importance": [
          "Time magazine named Dig Me Out one of the 100 greatest albums ever made — one of the clearest critical acknowledgements that Sleater-Kinney's influence extended far beyond indie rock.",
          "The album is a central document of the post-Riot Grrrl moment — showing that the political energy of the early 1990s could be channelled into musical precision rather than raw confrontation.",
          "Janet Weiss's drumming on Dig Me Out set a new standard for what a rock drummer could do without a bassist to anchor the rhythm — she became the rhythmic foundation of the entire record.",
          "Carrie Brownstein later co-created and starred in Portlandia — bringing the Pacific Northwest indie culture the band represented to a mainstream audience in a completely different medium."
      ],
      "historicalContext": "In 1997, alternative rock had become corporate. Nirvana was gone; grunge had been absorbed and commodified. Sleater-Kinney came from a DIY scene that had always operated outside the mainstream — Kill Rock Stars was an Olympia indie label — and Dig Me Out arrived as a deliberate rebuke to the idea that rock had settled. The Riot Grrrl movement had peaked and fractured; this album was part of what came next: music that carried the politics but wasn't defined by them.",
