    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "Have you ever heard a song used in a way that felt totally wrong for what the song is actually about? What was it, and what went wrong?",
        "activity": "With a partner, think of a movie, advertisement, or political event that used a famous song. Did the song fit the message, or was it misused? Share your example. (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "The title track was famously used as a patriotic anthem by political campaigns — before listening, think about why a song called 'Born in the U.S.A.' might not actually be patriotic.",
        "Listen to the lyrics of each track carefully. Springsteen's subject is almost always working people who are struggling — the music is big, but the stories are small.",
        "Notice how synthesizers dominate the sound. This was 1984, and Springsteen was consciously updating his rock sound with the era's most popular instrument.",
        "Pay attention to the arc of the album: it starts with defiance and ends with something closer to hope. Does it feel like a journey?"
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Born in the U.S.A. spent two years on the Billboard charts and sold over 30 million copies worldwide — one of the best-selling albums in history.",
        "The title track was appropriated as a patriotic anthem by Ronald Reagan's 1984 presidential campaign, which Springsteen publicly rejected — a landmark moment in the debate about artists' control of their own work.",
        "The album produced seven Top 10 singles, tying Michael Jackson's Thriller for the most from a single album at that time.",
        "It demonstrated that rock music about working-class suffering could reach a massive mainstream audience — and proved that the message could survive even when the audience misread it."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Born in the U.S.A. arrived in the summer of 1984, during Ronald Reagan's re-election campaign and a moment of intense American nationalism following the 1980 Iran hostage crisis and the U.S. boycott of the 1980 Olympics. The Vietnam War had ended only nine years earlier, and veterans were only beginning to be acknowledged publicly. Springsteen wrote many of these songs during his Nebraska sessions in 1982 — the era's economic recession had closed factories across the Rust Belt and left a generation of working-class Americans without prospects.",
