    "classroomSafeMode": true,
    "keyFacts": [
        "Recorded live over two nights — January 13 and 14, 1972 — at New Temple Missionary Baptist Church, Watts, Los Angeles.",
        "Mick Jagger and Charlie Watts of the Rolling Stones were in the audience for both recording nights.",
        "A film was also shot of the sessions by director Sydney Pollack, but technical problems prevented its release for 47 years — the documentary Amazing Grace was finally released in 2018, the year Aretha died.",
        "The album sold over two million copies in the U.S. alone, making it the best-selling gospel album in American history."
    ],
    "tracklist": [
        {
            "title": "Mary, Don't You Weep",
            "displayTitle": "Mary, Don't You Weep",
            "duration": "10:17",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "The album's most extended performance — a traditional spiritual that Aretha extends into a 10-minute journey of call-and-response, improvisation, and congregational ecstasy."
        },
        {
            "title": "Wholy Holy",
            "displayTitle": "Wholy Holy",
            "duration": "5:23",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A Marvin Gaye song transformed by Aretha and the choir into something that sounds like it was always a gospel standard."
        },
        {
            "title": "What a Friend We Have in Jesus",
            "displayTitle": "What a Friend We Have in Jesus",
            "duration": "4:04",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A classic 19th-century hymn given a slow, meditative treatment — notice how Aretha's vocal ornaments change the emotional weight of familiar words."
        },
        {
            "title": "Old Landmark",
            "displayTitle": "Old Landmark",
            "duration": "5:26",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "An up-tempo gospel number that showcases the choir and the congregation's physical response — by this point in the concert the church is fully on its feet."
        },
        {
            "title": "Give Yourself to Jesus",
            "displayTitle": "Give Yourself to Jesus",
            "duration": "4:14",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A quieter moment anchored by Aretha's piano playing, demonstrating that she was an accomplished instrumentalist as well as a vocalist."
        },
        {
            "title": "How I Got Over",
            "displayTitle": "How I Got Over",
            "duration": "3:38",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A Clara Ward composition — one of Aretha's idols. The performance is deeply personal and the choir's response is one of the album's most emotional moments."
        },
        {
            "title": "What a Friend We Have in Jesus (Reprise)",
            "displayTitle": "What a Friend We Have in Jesus (Reprise)",
            "duration": "1:07",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A brief, quiet return to close the first side — a moment of stillness after the emotional intensity that preceded it."
        },
        {
            "title": "Amazing Grace",
            "displayTitle": "Amazing Grace",
            "duration": "10:54",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "The centerpiece of the album — an almost 11-minute version of the most famous hymn in the English language. Aretha's father Reverend C.L. Franklin is heard weeping in the congregation. This performance alone justifies the album's place in history."
        },
        {
            "title": "Precious Memories",
            "displayTitle": "Precious Memories",
            "duration": "4:27",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A gentler hymn that provides emotional space after the overwhelming climax of 'Amazing Grace.'"
        },
        {
            "title": "Climbing Higher Mountains",
            "displayTitle": "Climbing Higher Mountains",
            "duration": "5:11",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "An up-tempo closer that brings the energy back up and sets the congregation on their feet again as the second night comes to its conclusion."
        },
        {
            "title": "God Will Take Care of You",
            "displayTitle": "God Will Take Care of You",
            "duration": "4:13",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A quiet, piano-led meditation that shows Aretha at her most intimate — just voice and keys, reassuring the congregation."
        },
        {
            "title": "Wholly Holy (Reprise)",
            "displayTitle": "Wholly Holy (Reprise)",
            "duration": "3:52",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "The album's final track returns to the Marvin Gaye composition from earlier, bringing the two-night concert to a circular, hymn-like close."
        }
    ],
    "keySongs": [
        {
            "title": "Amazing Grace",
            "note": "Listen for the moment around the five-minute mark when Aretha extends the melody in ways that sound entirely improvised. Notice how the choir and congregation respond — this is call-and-response in its purest form."
        },
        {
            "title": "Mary, Don't You Weep",
            "note": "This track runs over ten minutes. Notice how Aretha builds the emotional intensity across the full length — what techniques does she use to keep the energy escalating?"
        },
        {
            "title": "How I Got Over",
            "note": "This was written by Clara Ward, one of Aretha's greatest influences. Can you hear the difference in how she sings this song versus a hymn she didn't grow up with? Does personal connection change performance?"
        },
        {
            "title": "Old Landmark",
            "note": "This is the track where you can most clearly hear the congregation's physical response. Does knowing that the audience is dancing and shouting change how you experience the recording?"
        }
    ],
