    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "Can you think of an artist today who seems to belong to two very different musical worlds at once? How do they make that work?",
        "activity": "With a partner, name one artist who successfully crosses genre lines. What genres do they blend, and why do you think it works? (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Blondie came from the punk scene but were never a pure punk band — notice how many different styles appear on this single album.",
        "Pay attention to Debbie Harry's vocal delivery: she can be deadpan and cool on one track and enormous and anthemic on the next. How does she shift between registers?",
        "Listen for the moment when 'Heart of Glass' begins — notice how different the disco beat sounds from the punk tracks before it. Was that a brave choice in 1978?",
        "Ask yourself: is Parallel Lines a punk album, a pop album, or something else entirely? What does your answer depend on?"
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Parallel Lines was one of the first records to successfully bridge the gap between punk/new wave and mainstream pop radio, paving the way for the entire 1980s new wave movement.",
        "'Heart of Glass' became a transatlantic number-one hit and made Blondie genuine pop stars — while also angering some punk purists who saw disco as the enemy.",
        "Debbie Harry became one of the defining images of late-1970s alternative culture — her influence on female rock and pop artists has been continuous for nearly 50 years.",
        "Rolling Stone ranked Parallel Lines #140 on its list of the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time (2023 revision)."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Parallel Lines was released in September 1978, a moment when punk was already fading from its first burst and 'new wave' was becoming the industry's preferred label for anything coming from the punk scene that had commercial potential. Disco was at its commercial peak, and the culture war between punk and disco was fierce — punk fans regularly wore 'Disco Sucks' buttons. Blondie ignored the war entirely: 'Heart of Glass' was essentially a disco song, recorded by a band from CBGB, and it went to number one. That act of ignoring genre boundaries helped define the next decade.",
