    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Tusk cost approximately $1 million to make — one of the most expensive albums ever recorded at that time, mostly because Buckingham used the studio as a sonic laboratory.",
        "Fleetwood Mac's previous album, Rumours (1977), had sold over 40 million copies worldwide — Tusk was its follow-up, and almost no one was prepared for how different it would sound.",
        "Lindsey Buckingham recorded many tracks at home on a basic 8-track machine before bringing them to the professional studio, mixing raw home recordings with elaborate production.",
        "The title track, 'Tusk,' features the USC Trojan Marching Band recorded live at Dodger Stadium — an 112-piece marching band on a Fleetwood Mac record."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "One of the earliest examples of a major pop act using home recording techniques on a high-budget commercial release.",
        "Tusk challenged the assumption that a follow-up to a blockbuster album had to sound like the blockbuster — it remains a landmark statement of artistic independence.",
        "Though considered a commercial disappointment at the time (it only sold 4 million copies), critics have increasingly recognized it as the more adventurous and interesting record.",
        "Rolling Stone ranked it among the 500 Greatest Albums of All Time, and the 33⅓ book series devoted an entire volume to it, focusing on the Lindsey Buckingham creative control story."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Tusk was released in October 1979, at the close of a decade that had made Fleetwood Mac one of the most commercially dominant bands on Earth. Punk and new wave had spent two years attacking the polish and comfort of mainstream rock, and Buckingham was listening. The late 1970s were also the moment when home recording technology became accessible enough for a professional musician to use it deliberately — Tusk sits at that crossroads.",
