    "artistOverview": "Johnny Cash was one of the founding figures of American country music — a Sun Records artist alongside Elvis Presley and Jerry Lee Lewis, a member of the 'Million Dollar Quartet,' and one of the most distinctive voices in twentieth-century American music. By the early 1990s his commercial career had stalled, and most of the music industry had written him off. Producer Rick Rubin, known for his work with hard rock and hip hop acts, signed Cash to his new American Recordings label and recorded him alone — just voice and acoustic guitar — at Rubin's home in Los Angeles, producing one of the most critically celebrated late-career reinventions in music history.",
