    "historicalContext": "Spiderland was released in March 1991 — the same year as Nevermind, Ten, and Loveless. While those albums became immediate cultural events, Spiderland disappeared almost without a trace. Slint broke up before the record could gain any momentum. Over the following decade, musicians in post-rock, math rock, and experimental indie kept citing it as a crucial reference point, creating a strange situation: an album that became historically important entirely through word of mouth, years after its makers had moved on.",
