    "historicalContext": "Bitches Brew was recorded in August 1969 and released in April 1970, at a moment when rock music — particularly Hendrix, Sly Stone, and the psychedelic scene — was dominating popular culture and drawing audiences away from jazz. Davis responded not by resisting rock but by absorbing its electricity and rhythm into jazz. The album arrived in the same year as After the Gold Rush, Let It Be, and Black Sabbath's debut — a remarkable moment of genre-wide transformation. Many of Davis's existing jazz fans were alienated by the electric direction; the album found a new audience among rock listeners willing to follow him into uncharted territory.",
