    "beforeYouListen": [
        "This album was produced by Steve Albini — the same engineer who recorded Nirvana's In Utero. His approach is deliberately raw: no polish, no reverb, no softening. What you hear is exactly what happened in the room.",
        "PJ Harvey plays most of the instruments herself and wrote all the songs. She was 23 years old when this was recorded.",
        "The lyrics deal with obsession, desire, and emotional violence. They are intentionally confrontational — Harvey has described the album as a deliberate refusal to be sympathetic or likeable.",
        "A 33⅓ book on Rid of Me was written by Kate Schatz. The book examines what the album says about women, anger, and the limits of what rock music is supposed to sound like."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Rid of Me expanded the definition of what women in rock were expected to sound like — it was angry, abrasive, and unapologetic in ways that challenged the era's conventions.",
        "Steve Albini's production approach — live, dry, uncompressed — became one of the most influential recording philosophies in indie and alternative rock.",
        "The album is frequently cited alongside In Utero and Rid of Me as evidence that 1993 was a turning point when rawness and discomfort became legitimate artistic choices in mainstream alternative music.",
        "Rolling Stone ranked Rid of Me among the greatest albums ever made, and Harvey went on to win the Mercury Prize twice — no other artist has achieved that distinction."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Rid of Me was released in May 1993, two months before Nirvana's In Utero and in the same cultural moment that was reassessing what alternative rock could be. Produced by Steve Albini at Pachyderm Studio in Minnesota, it arrived at a time when the commercial success of grunge had opened space for more confrontational, less polished sounds. Harvey's refusal to soften her music or her persona was a deliberate artistic stance — she later described this period as one of total commitment to making music on her own terms.",
