    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "MF DOOM wore a mask and refused to show his face for his entire career. Why might an artist choose anonymity? What does hiding your face let you do that showing it doesn't?",
        "activity": "In pairs: if you had to perform under a made-up name and character — not your real self — what would your persona be and why? Share one with the group. (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "MF DOOM wore a metal mask at every public appearance and refused interviews that showed his face. He was playing a character based on the Marvel Comics villain Doctor Doom — and he took it seriously enough that when he couldn't appear at a show, he sometimes sent an impostor in the mask.",
        "Madlib is one of the most prolific producers in hip-hop. He digs through thousands of obscure records from all over the world — jazz, soul, film soundtracks, African music — and chops them into samples. Most of the beats on Madvillainy are built from records most people have never heard.",
        "The two of them made this album almost entirely by mail. DOOM would receive beats, write rhymes to them, and send back recordings. They rarely worked in the same room.",
        "The album was released on Stones Throw Records, a small independent label. It did not chart when it came out. It has since been recognised as one of the most important hip-hop albums ever made."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Madvillainy is widely considered one of the greatest hip-hop albums ever made — it demonstrated that underground rap could achieve the same level of artistic ambition as any mainstream release, without commercial compromise.",
        "MF DOOM's masked persona and alter-ego mythology influenced an entire generation of rappers who adopted characters, stage names, and constructed personas as artistic tools.",
        "Madlib's production approach — digging through obscure records worldwide, building deliberately lo-fi beat collages — became one of the defining aesthetics of underground and independent hip-hop.",
        "The album proved that a record could be made across physical distance, with minimal collaboration in real time, and still feel like a unified artistic vision — a model that became increasingly relevant in the digital era."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Madvillainy was released in March 2004, at a moment when mainstream hip-hop was dominated by commercial rap — production that prioritised radio hits, celebrity features, and commercial polish. DOOM and Madlib were doing the opposite: rejecting visibility, embracing obscurity, and making an album that demanded active listening. Stones Throw Records was part of a wave of small independent labels — alongside Def Jux, Anticon, and Rhymesayers — that were building an alternative to the major-label model of hip-hop. The album was a cult record on release and grew in reputation over the following decade to become one of the most studied albums in the genre.",
