    "soundAndStyle": {
        "genre": "Rock / Hard Rock / Disco / Punk",
        "mood": "Swaggering, urgent, playful, loose, occasionally menacing",
        "mainSounds": "Keith Richards's open-G guitar riff style, Charlie Watts's understated drumming, Jagger's sneering vocals, disco bass lines on 'Miss You', distorted guitars on 'Shattered'",
        "productionStyle": "Recorded quickly in Paris — raw and direct compared to the Stones' more elaborately produced 1970s work; the punk and disco influences are both audible in the production's speed and energy.",
        "energy": "High — the album contains the Stones' fastest song ('Shattered') and one of their most groove-driven ('Miss You'); very little filler",
        "keyIdea": "Some Girls is a band in their mid-30s refusing to slow down, and the result is one of the tightest albums they ever made."
    },
    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "Punk rock in 1977 was partly a rejection of older rock bands who seemed too comfortable and too big. If you were in a band that had been successful for 15 years, how would you respond to a new movement that said you were irrelevant?",
        "activity": "In pairs: name one artist or band who is still making interesting work after 20+ years of a career. What keeps them relevant? Share one idea with the group. (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "It's 1978. The Rolling Stones have been a band for 16 years. Punk rock arrived in 1976 and declared that classic rock bands like the Stones were bloated and boring. Disco was dominating the charts. Mick Jagger said he was trying to compete with both at once.",
        "Keith Richards was arrested for drug possession in Canada during the recording sessions and faced a possible prison sentence. He recorded guitar parts for the album while his legal future was uncertain.",
        "The Glimmer Twins — Jagger and Richards's production pseudonym — recorded Some Girls quickly in Paris. The speed shows: it's one of the most direct-sounding albums the Stones ever made.",
        "The title track caused genuine controversy on release — its lyrics include racial stereotypes that were considered offensive even in 1978, and Jagger has described the song as a satirical character study rather than a sincere statement. Teacher should be aware and is encouraged to frame this before playing."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Some Girls is widely regarded as the Rolling Stones' strongest album since Exile on Main St. (1972) and proof that a band from the 1960s could make vital rock music in the late 1970s.",
        "'Miss You' brought the Stones into the disco era without losing their rock identity — it was a genuine dancefloor hit at a time when rock and disco were considered opposites.",
        "The album's commercial success — it was the Stones' best-selling album in the United States until Tattoo You — demonstrated that the classic rock audience was still enormous even as punk tried to declare it obsolete.",
        "Keith Richards recorded his guitar parts during a period of serious legal jeopardy, and the rawness of his playing on tracks like 'Shattered' and 'Respectable' is often credited to that psychological pressure."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Some Girls was recorded in 1977 and released in June 1978, directly in the middle of the punk explosion. The Sex Pistols had broken up in January 1978; The Clash were releasing Give 'Em Enough Rope the same year. Disco was at its commercial peak, with Saturday Night Fever still dominating the charts. The Rolling Stones, formed in 1962, were widely seen by punk critics as exactly the kind of dinosaur rock the new movement was meant to destroy. Their response was to make a faster, tighter, more urgent album than anything they had released in years — and to add a disco single ('Miss You') that reached #1. Some Girls was the band refusing to accept the narrative that they were finished.",
