    "classroomSafeMode": true,
    "keyFacts": [
        "Some Girls was recorded in Paris in 1977 as punk rock was declaring classic rock bands obsolete and disco was dominating the charts — Jagger said he was trying to compete with both movements simultaneously.",
        "Keith Richards was arrested for drug possession in Canada during the recording sessions and was facing possible imprisonment; he recorded his guitar parts for the album while his legal future was uncertain.",
        "'Miss You' reached #1 in the United States and the UK, making it the Stones' first US chart-topper since 'Angie' in 1973 and demonstrating that a 16-year-old band could still compete with disco.",
        "The title track's lyrics provoked complaints from civil rights organisations and celebrities including Reverend Jesse Jackson — Jagger defended it as satirical, but the controversy made clear how much the song's racial references had offended."
    ],
