    "keySongs": [
        {
            "title": "Miss You",
            "note": "The Stones making a disco record — or at least a rock record that wants to be played in a disco. Bill Wyman's bass line is the whole song. Does it sound like the Rolling Stones to you, or does it sound like something else? What's the difference?"
        },
        {
            "title": "Beast of Burden",
            "note": "The slowest, most vulnerable song on an album full of fast, swaggering ones. This is the Rolling Stones asking not to be left. Does a tender song from a band known for attitude sound honest, or does it sound like a performance of tenderness?"
        },
        {
            "title": "Before They Make Me Run",
            "note": "Keith Richards, who was facing drug charges and potential prison, wrote and sang this himself. The lyric is about escaping before the authorities catch up. How much do you need to know about the context to feel what the song is about?"
        },
        {
            "title": "Shattered",
            "note": "The album's last track and its fastest — a word portrait of New York at its grittiest, recorded by a British band in Paris. The energy is pure punk. How does a band from 1962 sound like 1977 when they want to?"
        }
    ],
