    "beforeYouListen": [
        "This album sold almost nothing in 1974. By the 1980s it was one of the most cited influences in alternative rock. Ask yourself as you listen: why might listeners need time to catch up with a record?",
        "Chris Bell — Big Star's co-founder and co-lead guitarist — had already left the band by the time Radio City was made. Chilton recorded it essentially alone. Listen for whether it sounds like a solo record or a band record.",
        "Pay attention to the hooks — the moments where a melody grabs you. Power pop is built entirely on the hook. How quickly does each song announce its central melodic idea?",
        "Think about what 'Radio City' means as a title for an album that never got radio play. Is there irony there, or hope, or both?"
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Radio City is one of the founding texts of power pop — a genre built on concise, hook-driven rock songs that valued melody over showmanship.",
        "The Replacements wrote a song called 'Alex Chilton' in tribute, and R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe has named Big Star as the most important influence on his band — making this one of the most cited albums in indie rock history.",
        "The album's commercial failure — caused by Ardent's terrible distribution deal — became a case study in how a great record can disappear through institutional failure rather than artistic failure.",
        "Chilton's emotional directness and his willingness to make music that sounded both polished and personally raw was an enormous model for singer-songwriters and indie bands throughout the 80s and 90s."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Radio City was recorded in Memphis in late 1973 and released in 1974 on Ardent Records, a small local label with a catastrophic distribution deal that meant the album barely reached stores outside the South. The mid-70s music industry was dominated by stadium rock, progressive rock, and the emerging singer-songwriter movement — Big Star's concise, Beatles-influenced guitar pop had almost no commercial context. But the tapes circulated on cassette through college radio and independent record stores, and by the early 1980s, every underground band in America seemed to have heard them.",
