    "artistOverview": "AC/DC formed in Sydney, Australia in 1973, founded by brothers Malcolm and Angus Young along with Scottish-born vocalist Bon Scott. Their music strips hard rock to its most essential elements: two guitars, bass, drums, and a vocalist — no keyboards, no studio trickery, no genre experiments. By 1979 they had built a massive following in Australia and Europe and were on the verge of breaking through in the United States. Highway to Hell was their sixth album and their biggest commercial success to that point. Bon Scott died in February 1980 before the follow-up was recorded; Brian Johnson replaced him, and Back in Black became one of the best-selling albums in history.",
