    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Bon Scott — the vocalist on this album — died in February 1980, six months after this record came out. His replacement, Brian Johnson, made Back in Black with the band the same year. Today we're hearing Bon Scott at his peak.",
        "AC/DC deliberately avoids complexity: no keyboards, no synthesizers, no genre experiments. Listen for what that choice sounds like — and ask whether simplicity feels like a limitation or a strength.",
        "Pay attention to the rhythm guitar — Malcolm Young's playing is the foundation that everything else is built on. It rarely changes and it never lets up.",
        "Producer Mutt Lange made this sound bigger and cleaner than anything AC/DC had recorded before. Listen for the difference between a raw sound and a produced sound — and ask which serves this music better."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Highway to Hell was AC/DC's commercial breakthrough in the United States, and remains the definitive statement of what the band could do with Bon Scott on vocals.",
        "Bon Scott's death and the subsequent recording of Back in Black (one of the best-selling albums in history) made this album retroactively one of rock's most significant final statements.",
        "Producer Mutt Lange's approach to the album — keeping AC/DC's raw energy while making them sonically competitive on FM radio — became a template for hard rock production throughout the 1980s.",
        "The band's refusal to add complexity to their music — no keyboards, no orchestra, no genre experiments — proved that total commitment to a simple idea can be as artistically powerful as sophistication."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Highway to Hell came out in July 1979, as hard rock and heavy metal were becoming commercially dominant in the United States. Punk had declared that classic rock was over; AC/DC simply ignored punk and kept playing their version of amplified blues-rock. By 1979 they had worn down the resistance with years of relentless touring. Mutt Lange's production made them sound bigger than ever on the radio. Then, six months after the album's release, Bon Scott was dead — found in a parked car in London on February 19, 1980 — and the album became both a peak and a conclusion. Back in Black, the tribute record made with Brian Johnson, sold more copies than any AC/DC album. But Highway to Hell is where Bon Scott said everything he needed to say.",
