    "importance": [
        "Armed Forces marked Elvis Costello's arrival as a major artist — his third album in three years, each one more ambitious than the last.",
        "The album's political ambition — it engages with colonialism, fascism, and romantic manipulation simultaneously — established that new wave could be as intellectually serious as any rock genre.",
        "Nick Lowe's production approach influenced an enormous amount of British and American new wave production — clean, fast, and designed to capture the energy of a band playing in a room.",
        "Costello's density of ideas per square inch of song became a model for literate songwriters across genres — from alternative rock to indie pop to contemporary singer-songwriters."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Armed Forces came out in January 1979, at the height of British new wave's commercial and critical dominance. Punk had exploded two years earlier and was already fading; new wave absorbed its energy and added sophistication. Costello was making records at a pace that would be extraordinary in any era — three albums in three years, all critically acclaimed, all commercially significant. The album was initially called 'Emotional Fascism,' a title that gestures at its central concern: the ways in which love, politics, and power overlap and contaminate each other. Costello toured the US in 1978 and 1979 aggressively, and Armed Forces crossed over to significant American commercial success, reaching #10 on the Billboard 200.",
