    "classroomSafeMode": true,
    "keyFacts": [
        "EMI issued cease-and-desist letters immediately after the album leaked online — the legal threat turned it into an international news story.",
        "'Grey Tuesday' (February 24, 2004) saw over 400 websites host the album simultaneously as a civil disobedience protest; more than 100,000 copies were downloaded in 24 hours.",
        "The album uses a cappella tracks from Jay-Z's The Black Album combined exclusively with samples chopped from The Beatles' White Album — no other music was used.",
        "The Grey Album has never been officially released and cannot be purchased — it still exists only as a free download nearly 25 years after it was made."
    ],
    "keySongs": [
        {
            "title": "Encore",
            "note": "Jay-Z's bravado anthem rebuilt over a collage of Beatles samples — the juxtaposition is startling and immediately makes the listener hear both artists differently."
        },
        {
            "title": "December 4th",
            "note": "Jay-Z's autobiographical track sits over reimagined Beatles piano and strings, creating an unlikely but moving combination of two very different origin stories."
        },
        {
            "title": "99 Problems",
            "note": "Danger Mouse reconstructs the hard-rock feel of the original using Beatles guitar fragments — preserving the aggression while changing every source material."
        },
        {
            "title": "What More Can I Say",
            "note": "A showcase for Danger Mouse's editing skill — the Beatles samples are cut so precisely that they seem composed for Jay-Z's vocal, not borrowed from 1968."
        }
    ],
