    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Live Through This was released on April 12, 1994 — four days after Kurt Cobain died. Courtney Love had written every song before his death, but the timing made it almost impossible for critics and listeners to separate the two events.",
        "The album was produced by Sean Slade and Paul Q. Kolderie, who had also worked with Radiohead and Dinosaur Jr. The recording took place in late 1993, months before Cobain's death.",
        "Hole formed in Los Angeles in 1989. By the time this album was recorded, they had spent years in the underground before signing to DGC. Courtney Love has described Live Through This as the album she'd been building toward since the band began.",
        "The riot grrrl movement — feminist punk centred in Olympia, Washington and Washington DC — was at its height when this album came out. Hole were connected to but not exactly part of that scene; Love's approach was more theatrical and more deliberately commercial-sounding."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Live Through This is consistently ranked among the most important alternative rock albums of the 1990s — not despite its context but in addition to it.",
        "The album established Courtney Love as a major songwriter in her own right, separate from any association with Kurt Cobain — a fact that was difficult to argue in 1994 but has only become clearer with time.",
        "It expanded the sonic and emotional vocabulary available to female-fronted rock bands, demonstrating that anger, vulnerability, irony, and beauty could coexist in the same record.",
        "The album's chart success — reaching #52 in the US during a period of intense public hostility toward Love — showed that the music was strong enough to survive the surrounding noise."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Live Through This arrived in April 1994 at the exact moment when grunge was about to lose its most visible figure. Nirvana had changed mainstream rock, and alternative music was at the height of its cultural power — and also beginning to fracture under the weight of that power. Courtney Love had been a polarising figure in that world for years, and the coincidence of the album's release with Cobain's death turned what should have been a straightforward critical reception into something much more complicated. The album is now generally discussed as one of the defining records of its era, on terms entirely its own.",
