    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "If you were in a very successful band with one other person and then decided to go solo, what would you have to prove? Who would you have to prove it to — the public, critics, your former partner, or yourself?",
        "activity": "In pairs: think of one artist who was more famous as part of a group before going solo. Did the solo career make them seem more or less talented than they seemed in the group? Why? (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "George Michael was already one of the most famous people in the world when this album came out. Wham! — the duo he had formed with Andrew Ridgeley — had sold over 30 million records before they split in 1986. The question was whether any of that success was attributable to Michael specifically, or whether it was just the chemistry of the duo.",
        "Faith answers that question. Michael wrote every song, produced every track, and performed almost every instrument himself. He was 24 years old.",
        "The title track samples 'Twenty Flight Rock' by Eddie Cochran — a 1958 rockabilly hit. This was a deliberate choice: Michael was asserting his roots in American rock and roll at a moment when most British pop was heavily synthesizer-based.",
        "Faith became the first album by a white British artist to top the US R&B albums chart. It sold more than 25 million copies worldwide. Four of its singles reached #1 in the United States."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Faith was one of the best-selling albums of 1987 and 1988, and established George Michael as a solo artist entirely independent of his Wham! success — on his own terms, at his own pace.",
        "The album is a masterclass in self-produced pop: every element is controlled by the same person who wrote and sang it, and the result is one of the most cohesive pop records of the decade.",
        "Faith was the first album by a white British artist to reach #1 on the US R&B albums chart — a fact that says something both about Michael's musical range and about the commercial categories that pop music uses.",
        "George Michael's career after Faith — including Listen Without Prejudice Vol. 1 (1990) — showed a consistent willingness to prioritise artistic ambition over commercial safety; Faith is the foundation that gave him the freedom to do that."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Faith was released in October 1987, at the tail end of the decade that had defined the modern pop album. Michael Jackson's Thriller (1982) had set a bar for commercial ambition and artistic scale that the entire pop world was still responding to; Prince's Sign 'O' the Times was released in the same year as Faith and represented a different model of total-control pop artistry. George Michael was arriving late to the decade as a solo artist but early as a craftsman — Faith demonstrated that the polish and commercial precision of 1980s pop could accommodate genuine emotional depth and artistic seriousness. Its success was overwhelming, but its legacy is about the quality of the songs.",
