    "beforeYouListen": [
        "By 1970, the Grateful Dead were famous for playing shows that could last four or five hours, with single songs sometimes running 20 minutes. Their previous studio album — Aoxomoxoa (1969) — took over a year to record and nearly bankrupted them. Workingman's Dead was recorded in three weeks.",
        "The band was going through a difficult period: Phil Lesh's father was dying, several members were dealing with legal trouble related to a drug bust, and their management finances were in crisis. The album was made under real pressure.",
        "Lyricist Robert Hunter wrote most of the words for this album. Hunter was not a performing member of the band — he wrote the lyrics separately and Garcia and Weir set them to music. The collaboration between Garcia and Hunter produced most of the Dead's best-known material.",
        "The Grateful Dead were listening to two records while making this one: Déjà Vu by Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young — specifically the close harmonies — and Music from Big Pink by The Band, which showed that a psychedelic-era rock band could make something rooted in American country and folk tradition."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Workingman's Dead is the record that proved the Grateful Dead were songwriters and not just a live improvisation band — the songs stand completely on their own without any of the extended playing the band was famous for.",
        "The album was central to establishing country rock as a genre — alongside The Band and Flying Burrito Brothers, it showed that the folk and country roots of American music could be the basis for serious, contemporary rock.",
        "Robert Hunter's lyrics on this album — plain, narrative, rooted in American folk tale and myth — are widely regarded as some of the finest in rock music, and influenced country, folk, and Americana songwriting for decades.",
        "Workingman's Dead demonstrated that artistic restraint — choosing to do less — can be as powerful a creative decision as ambition and excess. It is one of the most important 'small' albums in rock history."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Workingman's Dead was released in June 1970, in one of the most eventful springs in American history. The Kent State shootings had happened in May; the US had just invaded Cambodia; the Woodstock moment of summer 1969 already felt like it belonged to another era. The counterculture was fracturing, and many musicians who had been part of the psychedelic experiment were pulling back toward something more rooted and quieter. The Grateful Dead made that turn more dramatically and more successfully than almost anyone. The album's title — Workingman's Dead — is a deliberate echo of the working-class American tradition, invoking a world of manual labour, outlaws, and ordinary life rather than the utopian communes and flower power of the previous few years.",
