    "keySongs": [
        {
            "title": "The Fear",
            "note": "Listen to the opening line: 'This is the sound of someone losing the plot.' Why does an album that's supposed to be a success story begin with that? What is Cocker telling you about what the album is going to be?"
        },
        {
            "title": "This Is Hardcore",
            "note": "The title track runs nearly eight minutes and builds slowly to an overwhelming orchestral climax. Listen for the moment when the production tips from lush into something almost suffocating. Is that effect intentional? What does it do to the emotional experience?"
        },
        {
            "title": "A Little Soul",
            "note": "The most emotionally exposed track on an otherwise guarded album. Cocker is talking to his absent father. Notice how the tone here is completely different from the rest of the record. Why does a song this vulnerable appear here, in the middle of an album about fame and disillusionment?"
        },
        {
            "title": "The Day After the Revolution",
            "note": "The album ends with a question rather than an answer. The revolution has happened — the success, the fame, the arrival. What comes after? Does the album resolve, or does it leave you with the same uncertainty it started with?"
        }
    ],
