        "mainSounds": "Electric guitar (minimal, droning, three-chord), bass, drums, organ, Jonathan Richman's voice (earnest, slightly off, completely committed)",
        "productionStyle": "Recorded in 1972–73 with John Cale — the production is deliberately minimal and rough. Cale knew not to over-produce Richman; the rawness is the point. The tapes sound like demos, which is partly why they feel so immediate.",
        "energy": "High and restless — even the slower tracks have a forward-leaning urgency. Richman sounds like he is in a hurry to tell you something important.",
        "keyIdea": "The Modern Lovers is about stripping rock music back to what it originally was: simple, direct, honest, and joyful. Richman's great subject is sincerity — believing things, feeling things, refusing to be cool about it."
