    "classroomSafeMode": true,
    "keyFacts": [
        "'Roadrunner' — a three-chord song about driving at night with the radio on — has been called one of the greatest rock songs ever made by critics from Lester Bangs to Greil Marcus. Its simplicity is the point: Richman wanted to make something that felt true, not impressive.",
        "The album was recorded in 1972–73 but not released until 1976 — four years later, by which time punk had happened and everyone recognised The Modern Lovers had anticipated it. The tapes sat in a drawer while rock music changed around them.",
        "Jerry Harrison (keyboards on this album) became a founding member of Talking Heads in 1975. David Robinson (drums) became a founding member of The Cars in 1976. The Modern Lovers were unknowingly training the musicians who would define the next decade of American rock.",
        "John Cale — who produced these sessions — was the viola player and co-founder of the Velvet Underground. Richman's band was produced by the person from the band Richman was trying to imitate. The irony was not lost on anyone."
    ],
