    "contentNotes": {
        "language": "strong",
        "themes": "Dark storytelling in the tradition of old folk ballads — teacher should pre-screen",
        "artworkConcern": "",
        "cleanVersionAvailable": "",
        "teacherDecision": "Teacher must pre-screen; frame as literary tradition of folk murder ballads"
    },
    "classroomSafeMode": false,
    "keyFacts": [
        "The murder ballad is one of the oldest forms of English and American folk song — stories of crime and consequence sung in communities for centuries before recording existed. Cave is working in a tradition that stretches back to medieval England and beyond.",
        "'Where the Wild Roses Grow' — a duet between Cave and Kylie Minogue — reached #1 in Australia and introduced both artists to completely new audiences. The pairing was widely considered an unlikely joke when announced; the result was one of the most celebrated Australian singles of the decade.",
        "PJ Harvey — herself one of the most significant artists of the 1990s — appears as a guest vocalist on 'Henry Lee.' The duet format allows Cave to enact the murder ballad's traditional structure of two voices telling the same story from different angles.",
        "The album ends with Bob Dylan's 'Death Is Not the End' — a song originally from Down in the Groove (1988) — sung with a large ensemble including Shane MacGowan. Cave's choice to end the album with a Dylan song is a statement about the tradition he considers himself part of."
    ],
    "tracklist": [
        {
            "title": "Song of Joy",
            "displayTitle": "Song of Joy",
            "duration": "7:30",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "The album's eight-minute opening track — a man visits a stranger's house and tells the story of his family's murder. Cave's baritone is at its most deliberate and ceremonial. The ironic title is the first signal that the album will use dark humour as a tool."
        },
        {
            "title": "Strange Fruit",
            "displayTitle": "Strange Fruit",
            "duration": "4:06",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A cover of the Billie Holiday standard about lynching in the American South. Cave includes it to anchor the album in the longest and darkest tradition of songs about violent death — this is not entertainment but witness."
        },
        {
            "title": "Henry Lee",
            "displayTitle": "Henry Lee",
            "duration": "4:16",
            "single": true,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "Duet with PJ Harvey. A traditional murder ballad (also known as 'Young Hunting') — a woman kills a man who is leaving her. Harvey sings the killer; Cave the victim. The traditional song structure — call and response between two voices — is used here with full dramatic effect."
        },
        {
            "title": "Lovely Creature",
            "displayTitle": "Lovely Creature",
            "duration": "3:58",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A quieter, more lyrical track — ostensibly a love song, but the love is possessive in a way that darkens its meaning. Cave uses the genre of love song to do murder ballad work."
        },
        {
            "title": "Where the Wild Roses Grow",
            "displayTitle": "Where the Wild Roses Grow",
            "duration": "3:56",
            "single": true,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "The album's most celebrated track — a duet with Kylie Minogue that reached #1 in Australia. A classic murder ballad structure: Minogue sings the victim; Cave the killer. Beautiful, formally perfect, and genuinely disturbing. The contrast between Minogue's pop-trained voice and the content is central to its effect."
        },
        {
            "title": "The Curse of Milhaven",
            "displayTitle": "The Curse of Milhaven",
            "duration": "5:56",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A fast, almost comic track about a compulsive killer in a small town — told from the murderer's perspective with an energy that veers toward dark humour. One of the album's most theatrically extreme moments."
        },
        {
            "title": "The Kindness of Strangers",
            "displayTitle": "The Kindness of Strangers",
            "duration": "6:07",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A slower, more elegiac track about a woman fleeing a dangerous situation — the murder here is a background presence rather than the main event. One of the album's more empathetic moments."
        },
        {
            "title": "Crow Jane",
            "displayTitle": "Crow Jane",
            "duration": "4:35",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "A blues-rooted track based on the traditional 'Crow Jane' story — a woman who shoots a man who wronged her. Cave is working squarely within the blues murder ballad tradition here."
        },
        {
            "title": "O'Malley's Bar",
            "displayTitle": "O'Malley's Bar",
            "duration": "14:25",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "Fourteen minutes. A man enters a bar and kills everyone in it, narrating in a calm, methodical, almost cheerful tone. This is the album's most extreme track — literary, darkly comic, genuinely uncomfortable. Its length and calm are deliberate. Teacher must preview and decide on presentation."
        },
        {
            "title": "Death Is Not the End",
            "displayTitle": "Death Is Not the End",
            "duration": "5:29",
            "single": false,
            "explicit": false,
            "hiddenFromStudentView": false,
            "teacherNote": "The album closes with a Bob Dylan song — a gospel-inflected ensemble piece with Shane MacGowan. After all the violence, Cave ends with the oldest consolation. Dylan's song is about transcendence. Cave's choice to end here is a statement about what the tradition of murder ballads was always for."
        }
    ],
    "keySongs": [
        {
            "title": "Where the Wild Roses Grow",
            "note": "A duet with Kylie Minogue — Cave as the killer, Minogue as the victim. The structure is a classic murder ballad: two voices, one story, told from both sides. Listen to what Minogue's voice does to the material. Why does that contrast work?"
        },
        {
            "title": "Henry Lee",
            "note": "A duet with PJ Harvey — based on a traditional folk song that is hundreds of years old. Cave and Harvey each take a role: the killer and the killed. Listen to how the traditional call-and-response structure of folk song becomes a dramatic form."
        },
        {
            "title": "Strange Fruit",
            "note": "Originally recorded by Billie Holiday in 1939 about lynching in the American South. Cave includes it to anchor the album in the longest tradition. What does it mean to hear this song here, in this context? What is Cave saying by including it?"
        },
        {
            "title": "Death Is Not the End",
            "note": "The album's last track is a Bob Dylan song performed with a full ensemble. After everything that came before, Cave ends with consolation. Does the ending change how you feel about the rest of the album? What is he saying by closing with this?"
        }
    ],
