    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "Think of an artist you discovered when they were small and underground, then watched become famous. Did their music change? Did your relationship to it change?",
        "activity": "With a partner: name one song that sounds simple on the surface but hits harder the more you pay attention. What do you notice on repeated listens? (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Elliott Smith had already made four albums on small indie labels before XO — he was a cult figure with a devoted underground following. This was his first record with a major label budget, and many of his fans were nervous about what that would mean.",
        "The year before XO, Smith performed 'Miss Misery' at the Academy Awards in a white suit, in front of a billion television viewers, after the song appeared in Good Will Hunting. He described the experience as surreal and uncomfortable — he did not see himself as a mainstream artist.",
        "The Beatles are all over XO — in the arrangements, the harmonies, the production choices. Smith was a lifelong obsessive who knew the catalog inside out. Listen for where the influence is obvious and where he transforms it into something entirely his own.",
        "Smith played almost every instrument on the album himself, layering his own vocals into harmonies and recording guitar, bass, piano, and drums in sequence. The lushness is the work of one person — which changes how it sounds once you know it."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "XO is one of the definitive albums of the late 1990s singer-songwriter revival — proof that intimate, emotionally precise songwriting could coexist with major label production without losing its soul.",
        "Smith's approach to layering acoustic and orchestral sounds influenced a generation of indie and chamber pop artists who followed him, from Sufjan Stevens to Phoebe Bridgers to Bon Iver.",
        "The album demonstrated that a major label deal could work in an artist's favor — the resources let Smith realize arrangements he had only imagined, producing his most sonically ambitious and emotionally complete work.",
        "Smith's Academy Award nomination and subsequent major label debut are a case study in the tension between artistic integrity and commercial exposure — a tension the club has explored with other artists and that remains central to how the music industry works."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "XO was released in August 1998, three years before the internet would fundamentally disrupt the music industry. The major label system was still at its peak power — signing Elliott Smith was a genuine artistic gamble for DreamWorks, which was better known for soundtracks and mainstream pop. Smith's cult following was real but small; his Academy Award performance had created a brief window of mainstream attention that DreamWorks was hoping to capitalize on. The album sold modestly by major label standards but was immediately recognized by critics as something unusual — a record that sounded like a major label production but felt like a private conversation.",
