    "artistOverview": "Can formed in Cologne, Germany in 1968 — a group of classically trained musicians who abandoned traditional structure to pursue something they called 'collective composition': improvised, groove-based music edited and shaped in the studio. Their lineup at the time of Tago Mago included Damo Suzuki, a Japanese singer they recruited off the street in Munich who had no prior recording experience; Michael Karoli on guitar; Holger Czukay on bass; Jaki Liebezeit on drums; and Irmin Schmidt on keyboards. They lived and recorded together at Nörvenich Castle, a medieval fortress outside Cologne, treating the recording process itself as a compositional tool. Tago Mago is their most extreme and celebrated statement — a double album of long, hypnotic pieces that sounds like nothing else in rock history.",
