    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "Have you ever listened to a song so long that it stopped feeling like a song and started feeling like a state of mind? What was it?",
        "activity": "In pairs: think of any experience where doing the same thing over and over produced something unexpected — a sport, a skill, a game, a piece of music. What did repetition unlock? (2 min)"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Can are from Cologne, Germany, and formed in 1968 — a group of musicians trained in classical and experimental composition who decided to apply those ideas to rock music. The result was something called 'Krautrock' — a loose term for the experimental German rock that emerged in the late 1960s and early 1970s.",
        "Damo Suzuki, who sings on this album, was a Japanese busker Can found performing on the street in Munich in 1970. They asked him to join the band that same night. He had no prior recording experience and sang in a stream-of-consciousness style he called 'instant composing' — words and sounds as texture rather than conventional lyrics.",
        "Tago Mago is a double album named after an island off the coast of Ibiza. It contains two tracks — 'Halleluwah' (18 minutes) and 'Aumgn' (17 minutes) — that are longer than most complete albums. These are not songs with verses and choruses. They are sustained sonic environments.",
        "The album was recorded at Nörvenich Castle, a medieval fortress outside Cologne where the band lived communally. They recorded continuously and used the studio editing process — cutting and reassembling tape — as a compositional technique. What you hear is as much an editing job as a performance."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Tago Mago is one of the foundational texts of experimental rock — an album that demonstrated what rock music could become if musicians abandoned verse-chorus structure and let groove, texture, and duration be the organizing principles.",
        "The Krautrock movement Can helped define — along with Neu!, Faust, Amon Düül II, and Kraftwerk — is one of the most influential currents in the history of alternative, electronic, and experimental music. Almost every significant experimental rock artist of the past fifty years has cited it.",
        "Jaki Liebezeit's drumming is studied as a model of how to create forward motion through locked, metronomic repetition — his influence runs from post-punk (PiL, Wire) through dance music (LCD Soundsystem, Caribou) to contemporary experimental music.",
        "The album's use of studio editing as composition — treating recorded sound as raw material to be assembled rather than a faithful document of performance — anticipates practices that became central to hip-hop production, electronic music, and experimental rock."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Tago Mago was released in 1971, the same year as Led Zeppelin IV, Marvin Gaye's What's Going On, and Carole King's Tapestry. The mainstream of popular music was moving toward polished production and commercial rock; Can were doing something that had almost no precedent and no obvious market. Krautrock was largely ignored outside Germany during its initial run — the albums sold modestly to a cult audience. The critical reappraisal came much later, driven largely by British musicians (John Lydon, Mark E. Smith, Brian Eno) who discovered the records in the late 1970s and identified them as crucial missing links in the history of experimental music. By the 1990s, Tago Mago was recognized as one of the most important rock albums ever made.",
