    "artistScene": "Reykjavik Experimental Scene · Icelandic Pop · UK Electronic Underground",
    "artistYearsActive": "1977 – present",
    "artistOverview": "Björk Guðmundsdóttir is an Icelandic singer, composer, and producer who began performing as a child and became internationally known as the lead singer of the Sugarcubes before launching a solo career in 1993. Her first three solo albums — Debut, Post, and Homogenic — are a trilogy that moved progressively toward electronic music and increasingly personal subject matter. Homogenic was made in Spain in 1997, during a period when Björk was living in London and had recently survived a deeply traumatic experience: a fan had sent her a letter bomb and then killed himself on video. The album's combination of electronic beats, orchestral strings, and themes of strength and vulnerability was a direct response to that trauma. It is widely considered her masterpiece.",
