    "classroomSafeMode": true,
    "keyFacts": [
        "In 1996, a fan mailed Björk a letter bomb and filmed himself killing himself afterward. The bomb was intercepted by police before it reached her. She has spoken about the experience as one that profoundly changed her sense of safety and her understanding of the cost of being a public figure.",
        "The album's strings were arranged by Eumir Deodato, a Brazilian musician best known for his jazz-funk interpretation of Richard Strauss's Also sprach Zarathustra, which became a hit in 1973. Björk chose him specifically for the warmth and earthiness he brings to string writing.",
        "Mark Bell, who co-produced Homogenic, was one half of LFO — a Leeds-based electronic duo whose 1990 track 'LFO' is considered a foundational text of UK rave music. Björk approached him because she wanted a collaborator who understood hard electronic production at a technical level she did not.",
        "Homogenic was recorded in El Cortijo studio in southern Spain. Björk has described the recording as a deliberate exile from London — a place to rebuild herself after trauma in a landscape that felt both alien and healing."
    ],
