    "keySongs": [
        {
            "title": "Jóga",
            "note": "Named for Björk's best friend. The strings build slowly then break apart and reassemble in the middle of the song in a way that is genuinely overwhelming. Listen for the moment the arrangement opens up — it is one of the most striking production choices on the album."
        },
        {
            "title": "Bachelorette",
            "note": "The most cinematic track on the album — an escalating story song with strings and beats that build together toward something operatic. The narrative is strange and beautiful; the production is perfectly matched to it."
        },
        {
            "title": "Hunter",
            "note": "The album opens with Björk positioning herself as hunter rather than prey. After what she had experienced, this is a deliberate statement. Listen to how the beat and strings work together to create the feeling of something armored and determined."
        },
        {
            "title": "All Is Full of Love",
            "note": "The closing track — and the most tender thing on an album that had just produced 'Pluto.' The shift from destruction to love is the album's emotional argument. Does the ending change how you feel about what came before?"
        }
    ],
