    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "If you could make a record with absolutely no limits — as long as you wanted, any style you chose, any collaborators — what would it sound like? What would you include that doesn't normally belong on a rock album?",
        "activity": "With a partner, think of one political issue you care about. How would you turn it into a song — and what genre would you use? You have 60 seconds."
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Sandinista! is a triple album — 36 tracks, 144 minutes. We will not hear all of it today, but it helps to know the full scale of what the Clash attempted.",
        "The album is named after the Sandinista National Liberation Front, a leftist political movement in Nicaragua that overthrew a U.S.-backed dictatorship in 1979.",
        "Notice how many different musical styles appear: punk, dub reggae, gospel, jazz, hip-hop (two years before The Message), children's music. Ask yourself whether it holds together.",
        "The Clash forced CBS Records to release this triple album at a single-album price, taking a loss on every copy sold. What does that tell you about what they valued?"
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Sandinista! is one of the earliest mainstream Western rock albums to incorporate hip-hop — 'The Magnificent Seven' predates many accepted milestones in rap-rock crossover.",
        "The album's triple-LP format at single-LP pricing was a deliberate political act — the band took no royalties on the first 200,000 copies to cover CBS's losses.",
        "It demonstrated that a band at the peak of its commercial power could make something completely uncommercial — and still be taken seriously.",
        "Sandinista! influenced the idea that political art can be joyful and playful as well as angry — not everything has to be a protest song to be political."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "Sandinista! arrived in December 1980, weeks after John Lennon's assassination and Ronald Reagan's election victory — a moment of genuine fear for many on the political left. The Clash responded by making something enormous, chaotic, and full of joy alongside the anger. The album's name honored a Nicaraguan revolutionary movement that had just succeeded, and its scope reflected a band that believed music could still change the world.",
