    "soundAndStyle": {
        "genre": "New Wave / Dance-Rock / Pop",
        "mood": "Joyful, campy, euphoric, retro-futurist, warm",
        "mainSounds": "Interlocking male-female vocal harmonies, chiming guitar, synthesizer textures, funk-inflected bass and drums, hand percussion",
        "productionStyle": "Polished and dance-floor-ready with Don Was's warmth and Nile Rodgers's funk discipline — cleaner and more open than early B-52s records",
        "energy": "High and celebratory throughout; built for dancing",
        "keyIdea": "A band processed grief by making the most joyful record of their career — and the joy is real, not forced."
    },
    "icebreaker": {
        "question": "Have you ever tried to feel happy or act happy when you were actually sad? What did that feel like — fake, helpful, or something more complicated?",
        "activity": "Name one song that makes you feel genuinely joyful and one song that helps you process sadness. Are they ever the same song?"
    },
    "beforeYouListen": [
        "Ricky Wilson, the band's guitarist and Cindy Wilson's brother, died of AIDS in 1985. The band didn't talk publicly about his illness while he was dying — AIDS was heavily stigmatized and the band was trying to protect him.",
        "This album was made after a long silence. Ask yourself as you listen: does the joy feel like escapism, like grief processed, or like defiance?",
        "Listen for how 'Love Shack' is structured — it's barely a traditional song. It's more like a collective shout where the architecture doesn't matter.",
        "Pay attention to the guitar playing by Keith Strickland, who switched from drums after Ricky's death. He had to become a different musician to fill the role."
    ],
    "importance": [
        "Cosmic Thing was a genuine comeback album — made after a four-year silence following the death of guitarist Ricky Wilson from AIDS in 1985.",
        "'Love Shack' became one of the most recognizable songs of the late 1980s and introduced the B-52s to an enormous audience that hadn't followed them since their debut.",
        "The album's combination of real grief and surface joy made it an unintentional but powerful document of the AIDS crisis era, when an entire generation was learning to carry loss.",
        "The B-52s were openly queer-identified at a time when that was not commercially viable — Cosmic Thing's massive success was also a small cultural victory."
    ],
    "historicalContext": "By 1989, the AIDS crisis had killed tens of thousands of Americans and devastated the creative communities of New York and other major cities. The B-52s had lost their founding guitarist Ricky Wilson to the disease in 1985 and spent years in paralysis and grief. Their decision to return with an album of dance-floor euphoria was, in context, an act of survival and defiance. 'Love Shack' and 'Roam' became massive hits and introduced the band to a new generation — but the album was made in the shadow of a loss the band had never been permitted to mourn publicly.",
